<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 94 / Rivers watchdog warns on pits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Pumping water out of abandoned mines in the Durham coalfield, which costs
British Coal Pounds 1m a year, must continue in order to avoid a serious
pollution threat to the River Wear, the National Rivers Authority warned
yesterday.
The river pollution watchdog said new information and results from
observation boreholes had led consultants to revise upwards their estimates
of the volume of polluted mine water which would enter the Wear should
pumping cease.
British Coal maintained pumping at nine places in central County Durham,
where deep mining ended long ago to protect coastal pits, which were the
Durham coalfield's last collieries. But with the pits' recent closure, it
now has no operational need to maintain the pumping network.
The NRA statement, based on research by consultant Wardell Armstrong, has
implications for the coal privatisation programme. Prospective purchasers
have warned the government that the historical liabilities of mining are
hampering sale prospects.
The authority yesterday joined a growing number of organisations expressing
concern that the coal bill does not spell out the new Coal Authority's
responsibility for the legacy of past mining including mine water pollution.
The government has said that the authority will take on these
responsibilities 'to the extent that they are not taken over by the private
sector'.
Wardell Armstrong estimates that if the central Durham pumping stops, 7.26m
gallons of mine water a day will eventually pour into the River Wear. Its
earlier estimate was 4.5m gallons.
</TEXT>
