<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 94 / Major pledges more cash for science
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON, IVOR OWEN and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Science enjoyed an unaccus-tomed day in the political limelight yesterday.
Mr John Major made his first big speech on science as prime minister -
promising to give research more money next year and a 'high priority' in
future spending plans.
Mr William Waldegrave, minister responsible for science, used a Commons
debate on research to announce that Pounds 15.4m would be allocated in
1994-95 to several initiatives including a scheme to encourage researchers
to collaborate with industry.
Some of the shine was taken off these announcements last night, however,
when Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, announced that
his department's chief adviser on science and technology would not be
replaced when he leaves next month.
Speaking to the parliamentary and scientific committee, Mr Major said that
science and engineering had 'too often been undervalued' in Britain.
'In the past 18 months we've done more to redefine science policy than in
the last 20 years,' he said. 'We have set a long-term course and now we must
hold to it.'
Mr Waldegrave said the government would know by the end of April which of
its research establishments are suitable for privatis-ation.
He said a specialist team had already begun a review and would be
recommending candidates for privatisation. Where privatisation was not
considered appropriate, the team would suggest more efficient working
arrangements. 'It is essential that Britain does not waste resources on
out-of-date structures,' he said.
</TEXT>
