<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 94 / Major pledges more cash for science
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Science enjoyed an unaccus-tomed day in the political limelight yesterday.
Mr John Major made his first big speech on science as prime minister -
promising to give research more money next year and a 'high priority' in
future spending plans.
Speaking to the parliamentary and scientific committee, Mr Major said that
science and engineering had 'too often been undervalued' in Britain.
'In the past 18 months we've done more to redefine science policy than in
the last 20 years,' he said. 'We have set a long-term course and now we must
hold to it.'
In a Commons debate on research, Mr William Waldegrave, minister responsible
for science, announced that Pounds 15.4m would be allocated in 1994-95 to
several initiatives, including a competitive scheme to encourage researchers
to collaborate with industry. He said the government would know by the end
of April which of its research establishments are suitable for
privatisation.
Mr Waldegrave said a specialist team had already begun a review and would be
recommending candidates for privatisation. Where privatisation was not
considered appropriate, the team would suggest more efficient working
arrangements. 'It is essential that Britain does not waste resources on
out-of-date structures,' he said.
Mr Michael Meacher, Labour spokesman on science, warned that the 'uprooting
of institutions' through privatisation and contracting out would undermine
staff morale.
The most innovative new scheme is for competitive research grants - called
Rewarding Our Potential Awards after the title of last year's white paper on
science.
</TEXT>
