<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 94 / CBI warns Labour on tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Labour party was warned by the Confederation of British Industry last
night that its plans to close tax loopholes would have damaging consequences
for investment, growth and employment.
Mr Howard Davies, CBI president, said measures proposed by Mr Gordon Brown,
the shadow chancellor, would raise an additional Pounds 3.6bn from business
over two years. That would represent an increase of almost 25 per cent in
the current corporation tax yield, which Labour would use for higher public
spending or lower personal taxes.
In CBI News, Mr Howard added: 'That kind of switch is precisely what the
economy does not need at a time when investment is historically low, and
consumption, both personal and public, correspondingly high.'
Mr Davies added that many of the measures proposed by Labour were also
individually objectionable. It would remove carry-forward and carry-back
provisions and reverse the introduction of the foreign income dividends
scheme.
In addition the proposed windfall tax on privatised utilities' profits would
probably push up charges to business users and also lead to cut-backs in
investment programmes.
</TEXT>
