<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 94 / Plans may boost GP fundholding
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is considering making it easier for family doctors to become
fundholders, in a move intended to inject fresh momentum into this element
of its health reforms.
The proportion of the population which is served by fundholders - family
doctors with budgets who buy hospital care for their patients - will rise to
around 33 per cent by April and 40 per cent by April next year.
But ministers are anxious to push this figure above 50 per cent before the
next general election, which must be held before April 1997. With Labour
pledged to abolish fundholding, ministers see the issue as a way of eroding
the electoral advantage Labour has traditionally enjoyed on health issues.
Ministers are convinced of their ability to persuade voters that Labour's
stance poses a severe threat to an innovation they maintain has brought
about improved standards of patient care.
A Labour document confirming the party's commitment to the abolition of
fundholding is expected shortly.
The main proposal being considered by ministers will give prospective
fundholders more choice over the range of treatments and services they would
be responsible for purchasing.
At present the budgets they are allocated cover a defined group of hospital
and community nursing services, such as health visiting and psychiatric
nursing.
Legislation may be introduced to enable fundholders to adopt more of a
pick-and-choose approach, controlling budgets only for some of the services
on the present list.
Such a move would be particularly likely if the range of services now
covered by the fundholding scheme is expanded, as many anticipate.
The government may also decide to lower from 7,000 to 6,000 the minimum
number of patients which GP practices or groups must have to qualify for the
fundholding scheme.
Ministers believe that this threshold is unlikely to fall below 6,000 for
the foreseeable future, however, because of the start-up costs which are
associated with becoming a fundholder.
The government has for some time been encouraging smaller GP practices to
band together in order to reach the minimum threshold.
A new batch of smaller practices intending to make this change is expected
to be announced shortly.
</TEXT>
<XX>
