FT  03 FEB 94 / BCCI auditing methods queried
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Inadequate auditing tech-niques were used by accountants Price Waterhouse to
check the books of the collapsed Bank of Credit and Commerce International,
a partner with the firm admitted at the Old Bailey yesterday.
Mr Simon Chapman, PW's audit manager for BCCI from 1986 to 1989, made the
admission during the trial of Mr Mohammed Baqi, former managing director of
Attock Oil.
The prosecution alleges Mr Baqi helped falsely inflate BCCI's profits by
signing bogus audit confirmation letters which pretended the oil company
owed the bank Dollars 90m (Pounds 60m). Mr Baqi denies 16 charges relating
to the furnishing of false information.
Mr Chapman was being questioned over the methods used by Price Waterhouse to
obtain such confirmations with BCCI's clients. Mr Stephen Solley QC, for Mr
Baqi, said PW's practice of allowing confirmation correspondence with Attock
Oil to go through BCCI was a 'serious inadequacy'.
Mr Chapman replied: 'We realised it was an inadequacy which we discussed
internally.' The practice was then tightened up, he said.
The trial continues today.
