<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 94 / Howard revises police proposals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, ALAN PIKE and ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday made significant changes to part of its flagship
law-and-order legislation, bowing to criticism that its proposals would
centralise control over the police and courts.
Mr Michael Howard, home secretary, abandoned plans in the police and
magistrates courts bill to have the people who chair police authorities
appointed by him, and agreed to introduce greater local flexibility in
determining the size of authorities.
Further concessions came from Lord Mackay, Lord Chancellor. He said
amendments to proposals, which have been described by Lord Taylor, Lord
Chief Justice, as threatening the judicial independence of justices' clerks,
would underline the government's commitment to independent, locally managed
courts.
Chairs of local magistrates' courts committees will continue to be appointed
by the committee without needing the Lord Chancellor's approval. Terms of
employment for justices' clerks will be left to local discretion - meaning
that Lord Mackay will have no power to impose fixed-term contracts or
performance-related pay - and many renewals of clerks' appointments will not
need Lord Mackay's approval.
The changes could be seen as an embarrassing reverse as the government tries
to demonstrate a firm grip on law-and-order issues. Ministers put a brave
face on the announcement, which was described by Downing Street as
'certainly not a climb-down or a U-turn'.
The need for changes became apparent when the bill was savaged by senior
Tories in the Lords last month. Lord Whitelaw, the former deputy prime
minister, who led the opposition from Conservative peers, said the bill
would now have his 'full support', virtually guaranteeing that it will pass
through the Lords without further significant changes.
However police staff associations remain opposed to proposed reductions in
the proportion of local authority representatives on police authorities.
The associations also oppose plans to set national objectives for police
forces and powers to amalgamate forces without public inquiries.
The local authority associations said that unless police authorities
contained a significant majority of democratically elected representatives
they would become unaccountable quangos.
Mr Tony Blair, shadow home secretary, said the announcement was 'a
humiliating retreat' which left the bill with 'no consistent rationale'.
</TEXT>
