<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 94 / Fleet chiefs slam brakes on company cars
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Many UK company car drivers who felt hard done by if required to keep their
cars for more than two years or 40,000 miles in the boom years of the 1980s
now have to drive more than 70,000 miles and wait four years for a
replacement.
And 84 per cent of companies with a turnover of Pounds 500m-plus are
intending to encourage employees to trade down to a cheaper car, provided it
is suitable for their job, according to a survey published today. Almost
half (48 per cent) of the smaller companies surveyed are planning similar
action.
Employees who trade down stand to make substantial savings on their personal
tax bills when a new tax system for company cars comes into effect in April.
It is based on a simple percentage of a car's purchase price rather than the
present system of bands for price and engine size.
To sweeten the pill however, a greater number of companies are allowing
drivers to trade up to a higher grade of car by making a personal
contribution to the cost.
The findings by the Monks Partnership, in its annual survey of companies'
car policies, show that 36 per cent of cars are being kept for more than
70,000 miles, up from 28 per cent in the previous year's study, and that
even directors are being offered less choice of car.
Even though they have to pay more tax on their company cars, fewer than one
in 10 drivers being offered a cash alternative is taking it up. The small
take-up on a cash alternative comes in spite of a near-doubling in the
percentage of surveyed companies making the offer.
The reduction in choice is being driven by greater cost-consciousness after
the recession, with more companies negotiating large discounts by
bulk-buying from a single manufacturer.
Among the Pounds 500m-plus turnover companies, 58 per cent are now offer-ing
a cash-for-car scheme, compared with 30 per cent 12 months ago. Only two out
of 171 companies had moved to compulsory cash-for-car policies however.
The survey makes some com-forting reading for BMW, the impending new owner
of Rover group.
BMWs are already twice as popular as Rovers among surveyed chief executives
and all other directors except the chairman, who still usually drives a
Jaguar.
The survey is widely regarded as representative of British business as a
whole. It was undertaken in December and January among a total of 171
companies, 62 of them with a turnover in excess of Pounds 500m.
Monks Company Car Policy UK 1994. Monks Partnership, Debden Green, Saffron
Walden, Essex CB11 3LX. Pounds 150.
</TEXT>
