<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 94 / Operations resume after fire at petrol additives plant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Operations resumed at Associated Octel's petrol additives plant (above) at
Ellesmere Port, Cheshire, yesterday after a blaze had destroyed a reaction
vessel and injured one worker and five firefighters. All the injured were
released from hospital after treatment, Ian Hamilton Fazey writes.
The fire started while emergency services were trying to stop a leak of
ethyl chloride. About 200 firefighters battled the blaze, which began at
8.30pm on Tuesday. A police helicopter flew over parts of Cheshire downwind
of the blaze warning people to stay indoors because hydrogen chloride vapour
was escaping. Associated Octel said the vapours dispersed quickly and were
not a danger.
The biggest concern was over a fire under a storage tank with a two-hour
protective coating. Firefighters put it out with 20 minutes to spare,
leaving other fires to burn while they tackled it. All fires were out by 8am
yesterday.
The accident prompted calls by residents and politicians for an independent
inquiry and relocation of the plant, which employs 1,650 people. The plant
is part of a petrochemical complex which includes Shell's Stanlow refinery
and dominates the south bank of the Manchester Ship Canal.
Mr Bob Larbey, corporate affairs manager, said: 'This was a major fire but
safety procedures worked. We do not yet know what caused the leak, but
automatic sniffing equipment detected it. The coating on the storage tank
also did its job. It is all very well calling for shutdown and relocation,
but we are a major employer. Exports from the site are worth about Pounds
250m a year.'
The company will use local stocks and supplies from abroad until the ethyl
chloride plant is rebuilt. Mr Larbey said the cost of the fire was still
unknown but the plant was fully insured.
</TEXT>
