<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 94 / Chairman of Tory group under fire
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir George Gardiner's future as chairman of the rightwing 92 Group of Tory
MPs looked in increasing doubt last night after the botched handling of an
abortive meeting with the prime minister.
MPs in the group were vociferous in condemning the way the engagement was
handled after Mr John Major had been angered by publicity suggesting he was
being offered terms for his survival as leader.
As rumours about a possible challenge to Sir George's chairmanship started
circulating, one prominent group member said the matter had been
'appallingly badly handled'. He said the meeting should have been cancelled
as soon as reports appeared that the group was demanding changes. The
outcome - the meeting was deferred after a few minutes - reflected badly on
Mr Major and the group.
Separately, the rightwing No Turning Back group of Tory MPs released a paper
arguing that a single currency would signal the end of the UK as a nation
state. It urged the government to guarantee there would be no return to the
European exchange rate mechanism.
A Conservative Europe 1994 and Beyond. The European Foundation, 61 Pall
Mall, London SW1Y 5HZ. Pounds 5.
