<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 94 / Australian payments deficit up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Australia's run of good economic news was reversed yesterday with the
publication of December balance of payments figures showing a
seasonally-adjusted current account deficit of ADollars 1.765bn (Pounds
830m), above market expectations, which had ranged around the ADollars 1.3bn
mark, writes Nikki Tait in Sydney.
It also represented a sharp deterioration from the revised November deficit
figure of ADollars 1.194bn.
The news, which initially sent the Australian dollar plunging, came less
than 24 hours after Mr Ralph Willis, federal treasurer, released some
sharply upgraded forecasts, saying economic prospects were 'the best for 30
years'. But by the end of the day, the currency and bond markets had
recouped most of their losses.
On Tuesday, Mr Willis revised the current account deficit estimate for
1993/4 downwards from ADollars 18bn to ADollars 17bn. Some economists fear
faster growth in Australia will bring balance of payments problems next
year.
The December data showed the balance of trade moved from a surplus of
ADollars 169m in November to a deficit of ADollars 505m last month, on a
seasonally-adjusted basis. Merchandise exports fell by 7 per cent, while
imports rose by 6 per cent.
</TEXT>
