<HEADLINE>
FT  03 FEB 94 / Germany's private steelmakers revolt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By QUENTIN PEEL and LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BONN, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Germany's private-sector steelmakers will today tell Mr Gunter Rexrodt, the
economics minister, that they are not prepared to make any further cuts in
production capacity for flat products, in spite of the European steel
crisis.
The big unsubsidised German producers, including Thyssen, Krupp-Hoesch and
Preussag, are up in arms over public-sector subsidies being provided to
other manufacturers, allowing them to maintain unwanted production capacity.
They are particularly furious about the rescue plan for the Klockner-Werke
steel plant in Bremen, which was formally signed on Tuesday, involving a
consortium led by the government of the city-state. The deal, which is under
investigation by the European Commission for hidden public-sector subsidies,
will maintain crude steel capacity of around 3m tonnes.
'This is the legalisation of a catastrophe,' one leading steel producer said
yesterday. 'It means that production capacity is being subsidised in both
Bremen and at Ekostahl (in east Germany), while private manufacturers have
already made huge capacity cuts without any subsidies at all.'
The private steel manufacturers are also angry and bitter about last
December's deal negotiated by all the 12 European Union member states,
allowing substantial subsidised production capacity to be maintained by the
state-owned steel companies in both Italy and Spain.
Today's meeting with Mr Rexrodt is intended to prepare the way for talks on
February 15 with Mr Karel Van Miert, the competition commissioner in
Brussels.
'We are looking for a restructuring concept from the industry, but we do not
have any wild expectations that we will get one,' a German Economics
Ministry spokesman said last night. 'We will be urging the private producers
that something more must happen.'
The response seems likely to be blunt. 'We will tell him that we have done
enough,' one producer said. 'None of the unsubsidised producers are prepared
to make more capacity cuts in flat products. That goes for Thyssen,
Krupp-Hoesch, and Preussag, as well as British Steel and Usinor-Sacilor in
France.'
The European Commission's warning on Tuesday that its steel rescue plan was
on the brink of collapse appears to have been aimed at pressuring the
private steelmakers to offer further cuts in production or face a
free-for-all which would lead to more bankruptcies.
'There is a clear message (to the private sector),' a spokesman for Mr Van
Miert said yesterday, 'if you don't do it now, you can forget it.'
'The real problem is structural,' he added. 'It is overcapacity.'
</TEXT>
