<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / International Company News: Hectic trading surprises dealers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Banesto lost 57 per cent of their pre-crisis value yesterday when
they were re-listed after a five-week suspension.
In hectic trading on Madrid's Bolsa, the stock closed at Pta855 after
opening at Pta800 and hitting a high of Pta894. At the closing price its
market value was about Pta147bn (Dollars 1bn). The stock was suspended at
Pta1,995 on December 28.
Nearly 5m Banesto shares were traded yesterday - at least 10 times more than
a high volume day before the suspension. The closing price surprised both
Bolsa dealers and Banesto's management.
Dealers said yesterday that foreigners were net sellers. They were matched
by domestic buyers willing to speculate that Banesto's value was above that
intimated by the rescue plan.
'If you are very rigorous, Banesto shares are worth at the very most
Pta700,' said Mr Juan Bastos, of Madrid securities house Ibersecurities.
'This has been a one day wonder, or it could be a month long wonder, but the
logic is that Banesto's price must come down,' said Mr Frederick Artessani,
head of foreign trading at stock brokers Benito y Monjardin.
</TEXT>
