<DATE>940202
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / International Company News: Volatile comeback for Banesto -
The bank's return to the bourse may be premature
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The resumption of share trading in Banesto, the troubled Spanish bank, on
Madrid's Bolsa yesterday was as volatile as its rescue plan is
controversial.
Despite a warning by Mr Alfredo Saenz, Banesto's provisional chairman, that
the true worth of the bank's share was its adjusted par value of Pta400,
down from Pta700, they opened at Pta800 amid heavy volume.
'It's an absolute punt, a casino bet,' said Madrid broker MrRobert Maxwell
whose firm, Maxwell and Espinosa, had been actively trading Banesto paper in
the off-the-floor 'grey' market before the stock was re-listed.
Banesto's existing shareholders, which include US institutions, the US
investment bank J. P. Morgan and former members of Banesto's board, were,
meanwhile, angered by the prospect that they would be barred from exercising
pre-emptiverights in the capital increase that forms part of the bank's
rescue plan.
The Corsair Fund, a portfolio managed by J. P. Morgan, invested Dollars 175m
in a Banesto rights issue last year, paying Pta1,900 a share, to acquire
some 8 per centof the bank's equity. The rescue plan's re-capitalisation
threatens to dilute the Corsair funds stake in Banesto to around 2 per cent.
'At this point in time I have no idea who has got what rights,' said a
lawyer representing large Banesto shareholders. 'I can't understand how the
shares are being quoted again when nobody knows the full details of a rescue
plan which has still to be approved by Banesto's annual general meeting.'
The trading volatility reflected the absence of any detailed statement about
Banesto's past problems, and about its future prospects. The bank's former
board, which was accused of gross mismanagement, was sacked by the Bank of
Spain on December 28. The new team appointed to run Banesto has established
that the bank has gross financing requirements of Pta605bn (Dollars 4.2bn).
It also mirrored intense speculation that Banestowill, as a result of the
rescue plan, end up as a subsidiary unit of one the large domestic banking
groups. Banco Bilbao Vizcaya, which has seconded senior executives,
including Mr Saenz, to provisionally run Banesto, is one candidate to
control the bank. Banco Santander, the strategic leader of Spanish banks, is
another.
The rescue plan, agreed between Mr Saenz, the Bank of Spain and the domestic
banks, has Banesto itself providing a total of Pta320bn towards restoring
its balance sheet. This will be done by allocating all its Pta244bn reserves
to provisions, reducing the par value of its individual shares and writing
down further provisions over time.
The Bank of Spain and the private banks will contribute to the rescue by
acquiring, on an equal basis, non-performing debtsthat Banesto is unable to
cover, to a value of Pta285bn. The domestic banks will also finance a
Pta180bn capital increase for Banesto, which will be underwritten on their
behalf by the Deposit Guarantee Fund, FGD.
Under the terms ofthe rescue plan, the FGD will publicly auction its Banesto
equity within a year. During the auction, which could take place as early as
this summer, the FGD will reserve a controlling tranche of Banesto shares
for sale to a domestic strategic buyer, either to a bank or to a pool of
banks.
A senior official saidthat only the FGD would underwrite the Pta180bn
capital increase, paying the par value of Pta400, because the private banks
were taking on a considerable portion of Banesto's bad debts. However, he
said existing shareholders could exercisetheir rights when the the FGD
auctioned its Banesto equity later this year.
As well as contesting the FGD's monopoly to re-capitalise Banesto, the
bank's largest existing shareholders are questioning the valuation of the
bank's assets, which the new management says have to be written down.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Banco Espanol de Credito.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>ESZ  Spain, EC.
</CN>
