<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / International Company News: Strong start to second big
Italian sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Italy's second big public privatisation was closed ahead of schedule last
night after heavy oversubscription for shares in Istituto Mobiliare
Italiano.
According to the Rome-based financial services group, about350,000
applications were received from Italian investors on Monday and Tuesday, the
first two days of the public offer.
The demand covered about 350m shares - almost five times the amount of stock
offered to domestic retail investors, who have been been allocated 75m of
the 200m IMI shares being floated.
The demand is well ahead of the first day's response to the sale of shares
in Credito Italiano last month, and suggests the government's privatisation
drive is gathering momentum.
The response to the IMI issue belies initial doubts among ministers that the
company would be hard to sell to retail investors because of its relative
unfamiliarity and lack of a big branch network.
