<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / International Company News: Victoire report lifts Suez
shares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN and RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Suez, one of France's largest holding companies, yesterday saw its shares
rise sharply on speculation that it is close to selling Victoire, the French
insurance company.
The shares closed FFr5.50higher at FFr361 following a newspaper report that
BAT Industries, the UK insurance and tobacco conglomerate, was poised to
acquire Victoire.
Suez and BAT declined to comment.
Victoire's ownership has been clouded by speculation since last autumn's
deal whereby Suez took full control of the company by acquiring the minority
stake held by Union des Assurances de Paris in part exchange for control of
Colonia, the German insurer.
Victoire is the fifth largest insurance company in France and has been
valued by analysts at about FFr15bn (Dollars 2.5bn). It was until recently
one of the more robust members of the recession-scarred French insurance
industry but last year suffered from the problems at Baltica, the troubled
Danish insurer in which it has a holding.
A sharp fall is expected in Victoire's 1993 net profits. It has reported a
41 per cent fall in net interim profits to FFr275m in the first half of the
year fromFFr470m in the same period of 1992.
