<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / International Company News: Profits at Kodak slide 33% in
fourth quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Eastman Kodak, the troubled US photographic equipment manufacturer,
yesterday reported a 33 per cent drop in fourth-quarter net income.
The drop, however, was due largely to lower profits at chemicals operations
which were recently spun off and one-time gains in 1992. The company
reported net earnings of Dollars 201m, or 61 cents a share, down from
Dollars 299m, or 92 cents, a year ago. Revenues dipped to Dollars 4.5bn from
Dollars 4.6bn.
Fourth-quarter earnings from continuing operations totalled Dollars 203m, or
62 cents, down from Dollars 251m, or 77 cents, in the same period of last
year, when the group had a 23 cents a share gain from the sale of Eastman
Kodak Credit Corporation and other investments.
Kodak, which has suffered a lacklustre profits record for years, ousted its
chairman, Mr Kay Whitmore, last summer and replaced him with Mr George
Fisher, formerly chairman of Motorola.
For the full year it reported a netloss of Dollars 1.5bn, or Dollars 4.62 a
share, due mainly to the adoption of new accounting standards, compared with
net earnings of Dollars 1.15bn, or Dollars 3.53, in 1992.
Mr Fi sher said that excluding special charges, 'the fundamentals show we
are beginning to make real progress in reducing our cost base, improving
productivity and strengthening our financial position'.
Earnings from operations in itsthree continuing businesses - imaging,
information and health - had increasedsignificantly for the year, including
a 20 per cent gain in the fourth quarter,as manufacturing productivity
improved and marketing, administration and research costs all declined.
He said the company was well ahead of its plan to achieve Dollars 2.8bn in
cash flow by the end of 1995, which would increase operating flexibility and
allow the company to pay down debt.
In the fourth quarter, earnings in the imaging division dipped 5 per cent,
from Dollars 316m to Dollars 299m, while information turned a Dollars 12m
loss into a Dollars 22m profit. Profits from the health care side rose 57
per cent, from Dollars 123m to Dollars 193m, while the discontinued
chemicals business saw a 59 per cent drop to Dollars 45m.
</TEXT>
