<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / UK Company News: Northern Rock tops Pounds 89m despite
heavier provisions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Northern Rock building society, the UK's 11th largest society, yesterday
reported a 29 per cent rise in pre-tax profits, from Pounds 69m to Pounds
89.3m in 1993, despite a 40 per cent increase in provisions for bad and
doubtful debts.
Mr Chris Sharp, managing director, attributed the rise in provisions,from
Pounds 12.2m to Pounds 17.1m, to a number of factors, including a fall in
the valuesof repossessions below the society's expectations.
Other factors reflected adjustments as a result of a switch in mortgage
indemnity guarantee insurancearrangements from Sun Alliance to Commercial
Union and the setting up of a general provisioning fund.
Mr Sharp said that this last move was an innovation for the society. 'We
intend to use highly profitable years, like 1993, to build up funds as a
buffer for the future.'
Mr John Wriglesworth, societiesanalyst at UBS, said that even though most
societies would be reporting markedly lower provisions for 1993 compared
with the previous year, the increase at Northern Rock showed a prudent
approach. He added that the growth in profits was particularly impressive as
it followed a sharp increase in 1992.
There was also substantial balance sheet growth, despite a year in which
societies have faced fierce competition both for mortgage lending and retail
savings.
Overal l mortgage balances rose by 20 per cent to Pounds 6bn (Pounds 5bn).
Retail receipts rose from Pounds 717m to Pounds 738m, helped by the
popularity of the society's postal accounts. Total assets grew from Pounds
6bn to Pounds 7.3bn.
The ratio of costs to total income fell to 35 per cent from 38 per cent.
</TEXT>
