FT  02 FEB 94 / UK Company News: Stronger UK demand helps Gardiner achieve
Pounds 4.02m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GERARD BAKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Steady growth in UK demand for home security helped Gardiner Group, the
security and surveillance equipment distributor, announce improved pre-tax
profits of Pounds 4.02m for the year to October 31.
The shares added 4 1/2 p yesterday to close at 33 1/2 p.
The comparative figure of Pounds 620,000 is restated in accordance with FRS
3 to include the Pounds 2.03m exceptional closure costs of the Spanish
subsidiary in 1992.
Turnover grew by 6.5 per cent to Pounds 78.6m (Pounds 73.8m),though on
continuing operations the rise was 10 per cent.
Earnings per share were 2.23p (0.17p) and a final dividend of 0.5p (0.19p)
is recommended, making a total of 0.73p (0.66p).
Mr Harvey Samson, chief executive, said thecompany had restored stability
after the dislocation caused by the discovery two years ago of falsified
accounting which led to the depart-ure of Mr Yashar Turgut, the then chief
execu-tive.
New accounting policies have been adopted for the company's asset valuation,
resulting in a reduction of net assets as at October 31 1992 from Pounds
13.3m to Pounds 6.75m. The change reduces depreciation costsand turns
pre-tax losses of Pounds 473,000 for that year into profits of Pounds
620,000.
Gardiner Security, the market-leading UK subsidiary, recorded strong sales
growth at stable margins. Mr Samson said that rising crime offered
substantialgrowth potential in the residential sector where fewer than one
in 10 homes hadsecurity systems.
The group's French and Scandinavian subsidiaries both performed well in
spite of recession. However, in Belgium and the Netherlands a harsh economic
climate made trading more difficult.
