<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / Bidders step up Paramount offers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Viacom and QVC Network, the protagonists in a Dollars 10bn (Pounds 6.60bn)
takeover battle for Paramount Communications, last night increased their
bids for the US film and publishing group in a photo-finish finale to the
five-month-long contest.
The complex new offers were not easily comparable, but Viacom's bid was
stronger in several important respects - including its cash element. Traders
were last night scrambling to put firm values on the two bids, which
appeared to be very close.
The new offers came just minutes before a 5pm New York time deadline set by
the Paramount board for final offers.
Shareholders will have until February 14 to consider the offers while the
market's initial verdict will be delivered today in the share prices of the
two bidders.
Viacom left unchanged its previous offer of Dollars 107 a share in cash for
50.1 per cent of the stock while QVC, headed by Mr Barry Diller, a prominent
film industry figure, raised the cash element of its bid from Dollars 92 a
share to Dollars 104 - still Dollars 3 a share below Viacom.
Both companies changed elements of their so-called second step merger - the
package of securities they are offering for the remaining 49.9 per cent of
Paramount's stock.
Viacom increased the value of its offer by several dollars in three ways: It
changed the right to receive Dollars 15.20 of convertible preference stock
yielding 5 per cent to Dollars 17.50 of 8 per cent debentures; it added 0.3
of a five year warrant to buy Viacom B stock at Dollars 70 a share; and it
improved the terms of its so-called contingent value rights (CVR) - an
element of its offer which has been popular with traders and which QVC
lacks. Under the CVR, Viacom guarantees to make up to shareholders the
amount its B shares trade below Dollars 48 in the first year after the
takeover, up to a maximum of Dollars 12. Previously, it had a floor of
Dollars 10.
QVC, by contrast, has increased the cash portion of its bid by Dollars 750m
by decreasing the value of its second-step offer. Paramount shareholders
would now get 1.24 a share of QVC stock, down from 1.43, and .2386 of
preferred stock, down from .32.
QVC said that in addition to increasing the cash portion of its bid, these
changes would reduce pressure on its publicly traded stock by reducing the
number of shares in its second step deal by 13.6 per cent.
</TEXT>
