<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / The Lex Column: Marks and Spencer
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Consumers will doubtless feel safe with a pension from Marks and Spencer,
but whether they will actually go out and buy one is another matter. Given
most people's reluctance, the quip that insurance is sold and not bought
carries a good deal of weight. It is a premise of the life industry that
without a salesman's insistent patter in the family home, clients will not
sign on the dotted line. Getting foot-dragging consumers to trot along to
the local M&amp;S store voluntarily may thus be a tall order.
Marks and Spencer is, however, touching on some important trends. Consumers
are finally catching on to the large commissions paid on life-related
products. Now that these are to be disclosed, pressure will mount to cut
charges. That will require a lower cost base, which M&amp;S is in a better
position to provide than traditional insurance sales forces, independent
advisers or even the banks. The industry may thus move to a much lower cost
base.
The other trend is towards simplicity. Whatever the marketing hype of fund
management groups, there can be little need for almost as many unit trusts
as there are quoted UK companies. Consumers may place a premium on
off-the-peg financial planning and simple products to go with it. This is
classic M&amp;S territory. While purists may quibble, the mass market may be
better served by a standardised M&amp;S financial product than the inappropriate
personal pensions many have thus far been sold. The only consolation for
life companies is that Marks and Spencers' inherent caution leaves a
breathing space for the industry.
</TEXT>
