<PROFILE>_AN-EBBDOAEZFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940202
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / Leading Article: The politics of local government
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
After the debacle over the poll tax, the government might have been wise to
proceed with caution on further changes in local government. Caution appears
to have been abandoned, however, with plans to replace the two-tier
structure of county and district councils in most of England with
single-tier unitary authorities. Local government reorganisation threatens
to create another political disaster for the Conservatives.
Already, there has been an embarrassing legal setback for the government's
plans. Last week, the High Court ruled that Mr John Gummer, the environment
secretary, had acted unlawfully by changing the remit of the Local
Government Commission which is in charge of the process. Mr Gummer had told
Sir John Banham, the commission's chairman, that the two-tier structure
should be abandoned in all but exceptional circumstances. Sir John had
become increasingly prone to recommending the status quo after finding
little popular support for reorganisation in many counties.
Now there is the danger of political setbacks. Most Conservative
backbenchers supported the idea of sweeping away the new counties such as
Avon, Cleveland and Humberside. Introduced in the 1974 local government
reorganisation, the newcomers have failed to win popular support. Yet
abolishing even these artificial counties has proved more difficult than
expected. There has been a heated debate among business leaders, MPs and
other local interests over the commission's proposals.
Greater heat
Much greater heat is likely to be generated over the abolition of
traditional shire counties such as Kent and Hampshire. If unitary
authorities are to be introduced across the country, these counties will
disappear in all but name. Abolishing them will be resisted by the
Conservative councillors who have run them - usually moderately efficiently
 -for much of the last 100 years. Grassroots Conservatives are beginning to
lobby against the whole idea.
And it will take only a handful of Conservative rebel MPs to derail the
creation of unitary authorities. The reorganisation plans for each county
must be placed before Parliament, where the government's majority is small
and fractious. The probability is that the votes will become increasingly
acrimonious and unpredictable.
Even where reorganisation goes ahead, the political repercussions will
continue. There will be substantial costs incurred in the transition, with
some staff made redundant or taking early retirement. New offices will be
needed, along with logos, identities, vehicle liveries and all the
paraphernalia of modern organisations. Estimates of the cost vary, but the
bill is likely to be about Pounds 1bn overall - one reason why business
support for reorganisation is ebbing away.
Voters' revenge
Much of the cost, however, will be passed on to the local taxpayer. And
since most of the new local authorities open for business in April 1996, the
higher council tax bills will arrive in the run-up to the next general
election. Voters might blame councils for the higher bills  - but with the
poll tax, they took their revenge on the government.
Small wonder, therefore, that Downing Street is considering a retreat. The
government is already reeling over its tax plans, accusations of public
fraud and corruption and a series of sexual scandals. Ahead lie likely
drubbings for the Conservatives in local authority elections and elections
for the European parliament. The latter also threaten to reopen the gulf
over Europe inside the Tory party. There is no stomach for a long battle
over local government reorganisation, with the likelihood of parliamentary
defeats.
The government missed an opportunity last summer to scale down the extent of
reorganisation. Mr Gummer suggested that the commission should restrict its
efforts to local authorities where there was demonstrable support for it.
Such a solution now offers the best exit route without complete loss of
face. The abolition of Cleveland, Avon and Humberside could then proceed,
preferably without creating unviably small replacements. In the rest of the
country, where some large cities might want unitary status, a petition
signed by a substantial proportion of the population would be needed to call
in the commission.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
