<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / Observer: Stay tooned?
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Has Ted Turner, the founder of Cable News Network, the world's first 24-hour
news network, joined the establishment at last? The question is raised by
CNN's failure to relay a major scoop - its interview with Sinn Fein leader
Gerry Adams, on Larry King Live - direct to its European audience.
The interview ran a day later and CNN used an actor to mouth Adams'
comments. So much for the idea that CNN has redefined news from 'something
that has happened to something that is happening'. Hard to believe that CNN,
which put its reputation on the line by reporting from Baghdad at the height
of the Gulf war, was kow-towing to the silly laws which prohibit the BBC and
ITV from broadcasting Adams' comments.
CNN International said yesterday that there was nothing unusual about its
behaviour. It has been based in London since 1985 and is licensed by the
Independent Television Commission, so it has always abided by Britain's
censorship rules. Perhaps. But there must be a sneaking suspicion that a
news network which can be watched by up to 1bn people doesn't want to
jeopardise its chances of increasing the European penetration of lucrative
ventures, such as its cartoon network, by upsetting officialdom.
</TEXT>
