FT  02 FEB 94 / Observer: History lesson
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
No one was more surprised at Observer's item, just before Christmas,
suggesting that plans for an NHS Lotto had foundered in 1988, than the staff
of the National Hospital Trust who were completing the 235th weekly draw.
True, the initial draw was halted for three months by the Crown Prosecution
Service which disputed Lovell White Durrant's advice that the lottery was
legal. The CPS eventually gave the go-ahead, much to the relief of Lovell's
Patrick Phillipps. He must be hoping that his latest gamble - advising
Rothschild's bid for the National Lottery - goes more smoothly.
For its part, the National Hospital Trust takes comfort from the new
freedoms allowed to existing lotteries in the National Lottery Act. No doubt
ministers have been reminded of the last time a National Lottery was allowed
to become a monopoly. John Blunt, having set up the first really successful
government lottery in 1710, subsequently devised the 'South Sea Bubble'
scheme to buy up, in part, the government's liability for Pounds 9m worth of
lottery prizes.
