<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / Observer: Teleological technik
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The wheel of fate comes full circle, if you give it enough time. Back in the
1950s BMW was in poorer shape than Rover ever was. It so confused its
customers - how could they trust a manufacturer which produced cheap
three-wheel bubble cars and large expensive Grand Tourers - that the
management wanted to put BMW into voluntary liquidation. They put the idea
to shareholders. Bavarian pride took over - the management got the push
instead.
Clearly BMW was fated to become a big name in British motoring terms. Ford
in Britain once produced a television advertisement which was never shown
because it was considered in poor taste. It featured a Spitfire speeding
through blue skies, while a voice-over declared: 'During the second world
war Ford built hundreds of thousands of aircraft engines in Britain. That's
why today the British do not have to say: Vorsprung durch Technik.' How
wrong they were.
</TEXT>
