<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / Long leash for a runaway economy: China's reforms are
deepening but inflation is a persistent and worrying threat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY WALKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Chinese leaders might have reason for self-congratulation as they prepare
for the annual Spring Festival holiday with a new batch of economic reforms
in place. But worries about inflation, an overheating economy and unrest
among peasants and industrial workers are casting a shadow over the
celebrations.
In the Year of the Dog, which begins on Thursday of next week, the
leadership's greatest challenge will almost certainly be to wring inflation
out of a surging economy while consolidating fiscal and monetary reform.
Failure to counter the prices spiral would risk further social distress,
especially in industrial towns and cities where workers in faltering state
industries are suffering considerable hardship.
For Mr Zhu Rongji, the senior vice-premier in charge of the economy, the
Chinese new year brings mixed blessings: financial reform is deepening but
inflation is casting a worrying shadow. He cannot be complacent about
achieving his oft-stated wish of a 'soft landing' for an economy which,
judging by the latest industrial production statistics, is continuing to
defy efforts to rein it in.
Industrial output in December grew by an astonishing 29.8, according to the
State Statistical Bureau, an increase of 11 per cent over November's rate of
growth. This acceleration surprised western economists in Beijing, and
indicates a quicker-than-expected response from industry to an easing of
credit restrictions in the last quarter of 1993.
Accompanying the burst in economic activity has been an increase in prices.
In December, the cost of living rose by an annualised 23.9 per cent in the
leading urban centres, compared with 21.9 per cent for the 12 months to
November.
In response, the leadership gave a clear sign last weekend that it is
anxious to curb a rampant economy. China's state council, or cabinet, said
it would not approve new investments in fixed assets this year beyond
existing projects. More than anything else, the capital spending spree has
contributed to unsustainable economic growth rates.
In 1993, fixed asset investment - in activities such as the construction of
economic development zones - grew by 47 per cent to Yuan115bn (Dollars
13.3bn) compared with the previous year. This year's capital spending target
of Yuan131bn represents a 14 per cent increase on last year, although the
state council decree may herald a lower increase.
But Mr Zhu and his colleagues know they must be careful at a time of
increasing unemployment - particularly in urban areas - not to apply the
brakes too harshly. 'What we want is a soft landing while the growth rate is
gradually lowered. If we drastically reduced the growth rate, we would have
to pay the cost of social stability,' Mr Zhu told Business Week magazine
recently.
Western officials in Beijing are giving the leadership the benefit of the
doubt about gradually bringing the economy under control. 'I do see positive
developments,' said the representative of an international bank. 'There has
been a switch in policy from emphasis on growth at all costs to stability
and consolidation.
'While they are entering the new year on the back of strong economic
activity, the trend for this year as a whole will be towards lower growth,'
he added. Mr Zhu and his colleagues have set a growth target of 9 per cent
for the year, down from 12.8 per cent in 1993. But western economists doubt
this target is attainable.
One worrying development for the leadership is that cost of living increases
in politically sensitive rural areas - peasants are in a sour mood about low
returns and high input costs - are catching up with those in urban centres.
In 1993, the national average increase in the cost of living was 14.5 per
cent: the rise was 15.7 per cent in the 35 main urban centres against 13.3
per cent in the countryside. In the past few years, the difference in the
cost of living between country and city has halved to about 2 per cent.
The authorities cannot afford to ignore threats to public order in a
fractious countryside. Surplus labour among the peasant population is
estimated at between 150m and 200m, and more than 200 incidents of rural
unrest were reported last year. While the grain harvest in 1993 was
bountiful, some hard-pressed farmers witheld grain they were obliged to sell
to the state in protest at low prices and rising seed and fertiliser costs.
These protests, which coincided with reports that the state was about to
raise the price of compulsorily acquired grain, spurred a round of panic
buying by consumers and steep price increases late last year. Local
authorities were obliged to dump government stocks of grain onto the market
and, in some cases, to introduce ceilings to dampen a price spiral.
In light of restiveness over price increases, the authorities have redoubled
efforts to curb monetary growth, with Mr Zhu demanding strict controls on
new credit at a national bankers' conference in Beijing late last month.
'You should not surpass these (loan) limits by even one cent,' said Mr Zhu,
who is also central bank governor.
Money supply figures for the fourth quarter last year have not yet dribbled
out of the Chinese bureaucracy. But they will almost certainly show a sharp
rise over the quarter to the end of September, as a panicky government
loosened the purse strings in response to urgent pleas from state industries
whose supplies of credit had been choked off.
The rate of M1 growth, the broader measure of monetary growth, had fallen
sharply from 34.2 per cent in June last year to 20.4 per cent in September
after a mid-year 16-point austerity programme. Banks were obliged to recall
loans for speculative activities, and new credit was squeezed tight.
Now, the Chinese economic reform programme faces a crucial year, in the view
of western officials. There is no question the leadership has set itself an
extraordinarily ambitious programme. It includes sweeping reforms of
banking, trade and of foreign exchange management. But the most difficult
challenges will be reforms to the tax system and state enterprises.
Tax changes are to include a complex new revenue-sharing arrangement between
Beijing and the provinces, along with a value-added tax (VAT) system that
would challenge the most sophisticated tax authorities. A western banker
said he doubted there were half a dozen officials in the tax bureau who
fully understood the new regime.
But Mr Zhu insists the government will muddle through. Senior officials say
tax reform will probably take about five years to implement and perfect. And
Chinese and foreign businesses would seem to be justified in their
apprehension about dealing with the tax authorities in what promises to be a
chaotic initial phase.
Reform of crumbling state enterprises poses huge problems, and plans to
tackle this vexed issue are murky. Officials have announced 100 enterprises
will be singled out for a process of corporatisation - a Chinese half-way
house to privatisation in which enterprises are detached from state control
 -but results are likely to be patchy, judging by past efforts.
The main question before policymakers this year will be the extent to which
they have to compromise on their central task of fighting inflation. The
views expressed by the World Bank in October hold good today. 'A premature
loosening of monetary policy at the present time could jeopardise the
hard-fought early gains on inflation and trigger a re-emergence of high
inflationary expectations,' wrote the bank's chief economist in Beijing.
Reforms are being implemented rapidly, but in the absence of low inflation,
Mr Zhu and his colleagues are continuing to live dangerously. They cannot
afford to ignore threats posed by inflation or signs of social unrest both
in the countryside and in urban centres. But there is limited room to
manoeuvre between what is politically expedient and the need to maintain
strict controls on monetary growth. Mr Zhu has shown he is prepared to risk
strong opposition to his austerity programme, but he cannot be sure that he
will prevail.
</TEXT>
