<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / Arts: Schumann and Friends - Concert
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MURRAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mini-festivals are not often so neatly planned as 'Schumann and Friends',
which is the brainchild of Raymond Leppard. Four Barbican concerts with the
English Chamber Orchestra, each including one of Schumann's symphonies,
filled out with less familiar pieces by him and with a wide variety of music
by friends and influential contemporaries: Mendelssohn, Brahms, Weber,
Hummel, Berlioz, Paganini. A judicious banquet, in fact.
On Monday the first concert - also broadcast on Radio 3 - showed him in
characteristic form. Generally brisk, unhesitating tempi, a strong sense of
continuity, a light touch that can become incisive but never strenuous; also
a certain shyness about Romantic expression, except where he has decided to
mould a passage with deliberate art.
He did that, for example, in the Larghetto of the First Symphony, which
sounded unspontaneous and slightly arch. The ECO strings, not at their most
polished here, might have achieved a more natural flow with an extra
rehearsal. On the other hand, his way with the Scherzo was very fetching.
Taking Schumann's 'molto vivace' at full value, he gave the main dance a
headlong sweep, almost falling over itself with excitement (often it seems a
more heavy-booted affair), while the contrasted Trio sections were suddenly
relaxed, cosy, even playful.
As a whole span, the symphony boasted a convincing gleam. So too Brahms's
evergreen 'Haydn' Variations, with any hint of village-band pomposity
scrubbed away, enhanced by an uncommon air of delicate introspection - true
to Brahms, of course, but usually underplayed in this work.
The novelties in the programme both had the American clarinettist Richard
Stolzman as soloist, joined by Thea King's basset horn in Mendelssohn's
indulgent little Konzertstuck. Mendelssohn himself described it as 'noodles
with cream', which is just how it sounded: long, glutinous strands of
duetting in thirds, with conventional roulades assigned to each soloist in
turn. Charmingly played, it fell pleasantly upon the ear, but once was
enough.
Weber's E-flat Concerto offered Stolzman far more opportunities for
deploying his fabulously subtle tone-colours and his genius for imaginative
phrasing - most of all in the Romance, which is really a rich concert-aria,
complete with hushed, dramatic recitative. The concerto also has sustained
bursts of mechanically brilliant virtuosity, in which even Stolzman slipped
twice or thrice in the effort of keeping up. But the heart of the
performance was in his fanciful expressive insights, and those were
breathtaking.
Remaining concerts: February 4, 5 and 8
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
