<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Publicise something weird and nasty and some medical and social workers will
promptly diagnose it all over the place. It happened with the sexual abuse
of children and now, it seems, Munchausen Syndrome By Proxy is being made to
look like an epidemic. Dispatches investigates. MSBP means drawing attention
to yourself by lying about or harming the people you look after. The
notorious case of the nurse, Beverley Alitt, who killed or attempted to
kill, the babies in her care has been followed by further diagnoses. Are
they accurate? (9.00 C4).
In Middlemarch on BBC2 the widowed Dorothea is now free to carry on with
hunky chunky Ladislaw, provided she is willing to forfeit the property she
would have inherited from nasty scheming Casaubon (9.30).
When Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH) made its 'Wishing Well Appeal' in
1987 it was so successful that it blighted other charities, some of which
claimed that GOSH raisedmore than it really needed. Sue Cook presents the
first of two programmes as the hospital moves towards trust status (9.30
BBC1).
</TEXT>
