<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / Carsberg to investigate island bus war
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir Bryan Carsberg, the director-general of fair trading, is to investigate
claims that a company with a fleet of only two buses is attempting to drive
a much larger company off an island by running services at a loss.
The Office of Fair Trading is to spend six months looking into bus services
on the island of Arran, off the Ayrshire coast, after a complaint by Western
Scottish, a company based on the mainland, that the two buses of Arran
Transport were running services in an anti-competitive manner.
The bus wars on Arran, which has fewer than 3,000 inhabitants, began in 1992
after Western Scottish tendered successfully to operate bus services on the
island with a subsidy from Strathclyde regional council.
It moved on to the island and supplanted Arran Transport, which had operated
bus services there since 1910.
Arran Transport, however, carried on providing its peak-time services,
registering them as unsubsidised services with the regional council and
thereby obliging it to withdraw its subsidy on those services from Western
Scottish.
'We had such a good response from the public that we had to go on running
the services,' said Mr Bob Haddow, Arran Transport's managing director.
'We are not losing money on these services and we welcome the
investigation.'
Mr Alan Wilson, managing director of Western Scottish, says Arran
Transport's buses start five minutes earlier than his own on the two
principal routes, which start at Brodick, the main town and ferry terminal.
Western Scottish has had to abandon some services because of the
competition.
The issue was referred to the OFT by Western Scottish in October 1992.
If the allegations against Arran Transport were sustained and Arran
Transport did not accept recommendations by the OFT, the matter could be
referred to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
'What is happening here is what is going on all over Britain but in
microcosm,' said Mr Haddow. 'It's about the threat that big companies can
roll up small ones so that the small firm goes out of business. Then the big
ones put up their fares.'
As for operating buses five minutes ahead of the Western Scottish services,
he says: 'When the Caledonian MacBrayne ferry arrives at the pier in Brodick
and everyone gets off there isn't any point hanging about.'
</TEXT>
