<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / Ferranti-Thomson wins Pounds 180m sonar contract
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A battle for dominance in the dwindling UK market for naval sonar equipment
has been won by the Franco-British joint venture Ferranti-Thomson Sonar
Systems with the award of a Pounds 180m contract to equip Royal Navy
submarines.
The decision, announced yesterday in a Commons written answer by Mr Jonathan
Aitken, defence procurement minister, brings to an end a three-year contest
with GEC-Marconi, the other main British company in the sector.
It is likely to accelerate moves towards the reorganisation of the sonar
sector into a larger Franco-British grouping.
The contract covers development of a new sonar system for nuclear-propelled
'hunter-killer' submarines and the supply of equipment for four of the Royal
Navy's Trafalgar class vessels.
The Ministry of Defence has abandoned plans to fit the new sonar on its five
older Swiftsure class submarines.
However, a further order is expected for other Trafalgar class boats. The
navy has seven in total and a decision is awaited on plans to produce more.
The submarines currently rely on a Plessey 'search and attack' sonar.
Plessey's naval business is now part of GEC-Marconi.
Yesterday's decision tilts the balance in a UK market in which
Ferranti-Thomson and GEC-Marconi have had roughly equal shares, and is
expected to herald a merger of the two operations.
Ferranti-Thomson's UK shareholder, Ferranti International, has been in
receivership since December. Negotiations have been under way on a plan to
sell its 50 per cent share to the French partner, Thomson-CSF, which would
then sell the holding to GEC-Marconi.
Ferranti-Thomson's activities could then be pooled with GEC-Marconi's and
with those of Thomson-CSF's French subsidiary Thomson Sintra Activite
Sous-Marines.
Thomson-CSF took its share in Ferranti's sonar business four years ago after
the UK group was rocked by fraud in its US subsidiary International Signal
and Control.
The French company has first refusal on the holding, but the Ministry of
Defence wants to maintain a UK partner.
If the plan goes ahead as expected, GEC-Marconi would in effect recover the
sonar business it has lost in recent years, including the latest submarine
contract, Sonar 2076, and the Sonar 2050 being fitted to Royal Navy
frigates.
GEC-Marconi's expected move closely resembles its takeover in 1990 of
Ferranti's airborne radar division. A Ferranti-led consortium was at that
time on the point of clinching the radar order for the Eurofighter project.
</TEXT>
