<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / Surveyors' orders point to upturn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Further evidence that construction activity is on the brink of recovery
emerged yesterday with the publication of a survey of industry order books.
This showed that order books of quantity surveyors fell 10 per cent last
year although the rate of decline slowed considerably during the final three
months.
Much of the work done by quantity surveyors occurs early in the building
process and so provides a good guide to future construction orders.
The Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors, which carried out the survey,
said the industry was suffering from overcapacity. This was likely to cause
further job losses 'as it continues to adjust to lower workload levels',
said Mr Christopher Vickers, a senior partner at quantity surveyors EC
Harris and construction spokesman for the institution. He added: 'Intense
competition for work combined with rising material costs will add further
pressure to building firms over the next six to nine months.' The
institution said the workload of surveyors fell 3 per cent in the final
quarter of last year compared with the previous three months.
QS Workload Statistics, Library and Information Service, RICS. Pounds 15.
Telephone 071-222-7000.
</TEXT>
