<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / MMC findings set to be opened up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Industry and consumer organisations will have more opportunity to comment on
monopoly inquiry findings before the government decides whether to accept
recommendations bythe Monopolies and Mergers Commission, Mr Michael
Heseltine indicated yesterday.
Speaking to the Confederation of British Industry in London, the trade and
industry secretary said that consultation could be a vital step in weighing
policy alternatives.
He said that those involved had the benefit of knowing the full extent of
the commission's analysis and findings. The procedure wasparticularly useful
for reports which might lead to substantial change.
Mr Heseltine said consultation on the recent gas report had proved
invaluable in ensuring that his decisions were taken with the best possible
knowledge of their likely effects. He rejected the recommendation that
British Gas should be required to sell off its trading business by early
1997. Instead he decided that British Gas should operate its pipeline and
trading arms as separate businesses.
Pressure for the commission's broader findings to be opened up to wider
scrutiny has increased in recent years.
</TEXT>
