<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / Smith pledges not to nationalise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, yesterday gave the party's modernisers a
significant boost by ruling out renationalisation and linking improved
social services firmly to economic growth.
In a wide-ranging interview, Mr Smith also gave a clear endorsement of the
profit motive and insisted that Labour could deliver a fairer Britain
without big tax increases.
'I do not believe the government should run industry or own industry. But I
do believe the government has got to work with industry. We have got to
create a partnership,' he told the Daily Mirror.
'I want companies to be prosperous, to make profits, to pay their workers
well. And I want them to be a success story for Britain,' he said.
Mr Smith said a future Labour government would introduce a fairer tax system
which would remove much of the burden from 'ordinary people.'
But he warned that the party would be unable to deliver improvements in
public services unless it succeeded in promoting a sustained economic
recovery.
'If we get good steady economic growth we can afford good social services,'
he said. 'If we don't get good economic growth we can't. It is as simple as
that.'
Mr Smith's comments will give heart to Labour's modernisers, led by Mr
Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor, who favour undogmatic policies focusing on
good economic management.
However, the interview will dismay leftwing groups, which last week tabled a
Commons motion calling for a commitment to more traditional Labour policies.
Mr Smith was scathing about the Conservative record on taxation, which had
opened up opportunities for Labour to win support for its pro-posals for a
'fairer' tax system.
'It is the Tories who are the dogmatic party now,' he said. 'Privatisation
has gone too far. I cannot find anybody who believes in railway
privatisation. It is almost as if this government is going around saying -
what can we do to annoy you?'
</TEXT>
