<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / Insurers win hint of concession
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is prepared to consider 'sympathetically' suggestions by the
insurance industry that it should be given the option of accounting for the
new 3 per cent tax introduced in the Budget on a 'premium-written basis'.
Sir John Cope, the paymaster-general, told the Commons last night that the
use of this procedure would tie in more closely with many of the accounting
arrangements in the industry.
He said the implications, including whether gross premiums rather than net
premiums should be the basis of the tax, required further study by
government and industry.
The new tax, which begins in October, will apply to most general insurance
where the insured risk is in the UK, and is expected to yield Pounds 775m in
its first year of operation.
Sir John, speaking in the committee stage of the finance bill, confirmed
that the insurance element in subscriptions paid to the AA, RAC and other
motoring organisations would be subject to the new tax.
Mr Alistair Darling, Labour spokesman on financial services, warned that
because of the new tax there would be a 'substantial risk' that many people
would under-insure when taking out policies on their homes and possessions.
A Labour attempt to delay the imposition of the insurance premium tax until
a report had been presented to parliament on its effect on policyholders and
the future of the industry was defeated by a government majority of 42
(327-285).
Clauses in the bill authorising the insurance premium tax,and the increase
in income tax arising from the non-indexation of of personal allowances were
approved by government majorities of 37.
The government secured a majority of 27 (315-288) authorising the use of the
parliamentary guillotine to ensure that the committee stage of the bill is
completed by March 29.
Mrs Margaret Beckett, Labour deputy leader, accused the government of
imposing a timetable designed to prevent Labour mounting a new challenge
against the imposition of VAT on domestic fuel.
</TEXT>
