<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / Dorrell defends taxation reforms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Stephen Dorrell, financial secretary to the Treasury, yesterday tried to
regain the initiative in the debate over Tory taxation policy by arguing
that the government had introduced tax reforms that improve economic
efficiency.
In a speech to the Tory Bow Group, Mr Dorrell attacked opposition criticisms
that the government had harmed the economy by raising taxes. He claimed that
Tory tax policy since 1979 had promoted economic efficiency by sharpening
incentives and rewarding innovation and initiative.
'It is in the interests of all of us to structure the tax system so as to do
minimum damage to the incentives to create wealth,' he said. 'That means
shifting the balance of the tax burden from direct to indirect tax.'
Mr Dorrell's speech follows a prolonged attack by Labour on tax increases
and cuts in public spending announced in the last two Budgets.
He focused on what he saw as three key improvements. He claimed that the
government had sharpened incentives for workers by boosting the amount of
marginal earnings kept after tax. He said an 18 per cent cut in the
corporation tax rate had boosted business.
Finally, he argued that the government had boosted incentives for savers by
cutting marginal rates of tax on savings income and introducing tax
incentives through the Pep and Tessa schemes.
Mr Norman Lamont, the former chancellor, yesterday hinted that the
government's long-term reviews of public spending had not been implemented
rigorously enough.
Mr Lamont said: 'It is extremely important that these long-term reviews are
carried out and are implemented.'
He did not specify what areas of the public spending review he had in mind.
Treasury officials say the review was used to structure spending for the
social security, health and education departments and the Home Office in the
last Budget.
