FT  02 FEB 94 / Labour fighter for women dies at 70
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ms Jo Richardson, the leftwing Labour MP for Barking, best known as a
campaigner for women's rights, diedyesterday after a long illness aged 70.
Her death, which increases the government's Commons majority temporarily to
19, leaves the Conservatives facing the prospect of two by-elections in
quick succession in safe Labour seats. They come in the run-up to this
year's local and European elections.
Mr James Boyce, the Labour MP for Rotherham, died just a week ago.
The Conservative party's low standing in opinion polls and the location of
Ms Richardson's seatin east London may cause concern that the contest could
produce another strong electoral showing by the extreme right.
Last September, the far-right British National party won its first-ever
local authority seat in the east London borough of Tower Hamlets.
Ms Richardson, who entered parliament 20 years ago this month, held her east
London seat in 1992 with an increased majority of 6,268 over the
Conservative candidate. The extreme right did not fight the seat.
A life-long leftwinger, she sat on Labour's national executive committee for
12 years until 1991 and was a member of the shadow cabinet from 1987 to
1992. She would probably have been Britain's first minister for women if
Labour had won the last general election.
Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, said yesterday: 'No one in the history of
our party has fought harder or to greater effect on behalf of women.'
In 1986, she opposed the expulsion from the Labour party of alleged members
of Militant in Liverpool City Council.
</TEXT>
