<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / Howard yields to critics of police reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN and ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government will today announce that it intends to dilute its proposed
police reforms following strong opposition in the Lords last month.
Mr Michael Howard,home secretary, will surrender his right to appoint people
to chair police authorities in England and Wales as part of a package of
changes intend to appease critics and save the police and magistrates courts
bill.
The bill proposedreplacing police authorities - now made up of two-thirds
local councillors andone-third magistrates - with smaller, 16-strong bodies,
each containing eight councillors, three magistrates and five other members
who would be appointed by the home secretary.
Under the changes to be announced today Mr Howard will, as well as
surrendering the right to appoint the nominee for the chair, move away from
the principle that all committees must be 16-strong.
The government now believes that the precise size should be determined by
local conditions, but with councillors always having parity with the other
members. This means that, on authorities with an uneven number of members,
one of the councillors could expect to take the chair.
Without this change, local authorities wouldhave regarded the abandonment of
the right to appoint a chair as meaningless if, after an 8-8 tie, the
decision reverted to the home secretary.
The needto amend the bill on matters of central principle will be an
embarrassment for the government. Senior police officers and local authority
representatives have consistently opposed the changes to police authorities
since they were outlined last March. But ministers did not appear to
recognise the full depth of concern until the bill came under attack from
such heavyweight figures as Lord Whitelaw,the former home secretary and
deputy prime minister.
It remains unclearto what extent today's concessions will eliminate
opposition to the bill. Some critics oppose giving the home secretary any
direct powers of appointment to police authorities. Although an arms-length
selection process is planned, and Mr Howard has stressed that appointees
will not be party-political, there are concerns that it could become a step
towards a national police structure under government control.
The bill also faces attack over proposals which critics say would reduce the
independence of magistrates' clerks.
</TEXT>
