<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / Failures in auditing 'widespread': Profession reports lapses
to DTI
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Many accountants are failing to meet professional standards when carrying
out audits, says a confidential report sent to the government by chartered
accountancy bodies.
Nearly two-thirds of firms inspected in the year to last September were the
subject of detailed regulatory reports triggered by concerns over issues
such as the quality of auditing or compliance with regulations.
The report, which has been obtained by the FT, covers the second year of the
regime of self-regulation for auditors. It was recently sent to the
Department of Trade and Industry and its findings are due to be made public
soon.
It interprets most of the breaches as relatively minor and applicable
primarily to smaller firms, but the figures raise serious questions about
the quality of auditing conducted by the 10,600 firms registered.
The report says many firms have failed to provide evidence of the work they
have carried out, or have not established procedures designed to assure the
quality of their auditing.
It describes inspections to 312 firms by the Joint Monitoring Unit, which is
controlled by the three chartered accountancy bodies covering England,
Wales, Scotland and Ireland.
So far 263 of these visits have been written up in completed reports to the
profession's regulatory committees, of which 197 are in 'long form'  -
normally meaning that the firms need to take remedial action.
The most common problems identified were with firms' audit procedures,
performance of individual assignments, quality assurance procedures and
independence.
Most of these issues applied to smaller firms and those without listed
clients. For the larger firms, the inspectors concluded that most problems
were human failures rather than deficiencies in systems and procedures.
The report concludes: 'While it is clear that the majority of registered
auditors aretaking the need to comply with the regulations seriously, it is
also clear thatmany firms have not reached the standard of work envisaged by
current auditing standards and guidelines.'
It stresses that the problems identified havenot 'necessarily' affected the
audit opinion, and that in most cases non-compliance 'would not' have
resulted in any interested party suffering loss.
Across mainland Britain since October 1991, 111 firms have had their audit
registration withdrawn or revoked, 15 have been refused registration, 19 are
subject to restrictions on auditing and 1,904 have voluntary withdrawn
applications to be registered.
The report shows that complaints against auditors in England and Wales rose
to 268 in the year to last September, up from 175 in the previous year.
Total regulatory costs for 1993 were Pounds 4.2m, and are projected at
Pounds 4.7m for 1994. Just 147 firms audit all 2,300 listed companies in the
UK, and 18firms audit 2,044 of these.
The report, which will form the basis for a review by the DTI of the
effectiveness of self-regulation, suggests concentrating future inspections
on the issues identified as causing the greatest problems.
</TEXT>
<XX>
