FT  02 FEB 94 / Unions postpone protest over pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Union leaders representing Britain's 5.8m public-sector workers decided
yesterday to hold back from calling any protest action against the
government's three-year freeze on the pay bill.
Instead, they are to wait for the results of the public pay review body
reports, which are due shortly, and the government's response to them.
Union leaders warned that support exists in principle for the calling of a
day of action to highlight threats to public services and jobs.
A private opinion poll commissioned by the Trades Union Congress found there
was substantial support among both private-sector and public-sector workers
for some form of protest. 'The form a 'public-sector day' will take and the
most appropriate timing will be the subject of further discussion between
unions,' the TUC said in a statement. Union leaders, however, dropped the
idea of a day of action on April 11.
The TUC added that it was clear that the pay policy, tax rises,
market-testing and contracting-out were 'likely to lead to industrial
action'.
