<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / Gooda Names may face delay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Names on the lossmaking Gooda Walker syndicates at Lloyd's could face long
delays in their legal action due to start in April following an application
for an adjournment by defendants in the case.
More than 3,000 Gooda Names - individuals whose assets have traditionally
backed the Lloyd's insurance market - are taking action against more than 70
agents in an attempt to recover losses of more than Pounds 550m.
The adjournment application, lodged with the courts on Friday by Elborne
Mitchell, the agents' solicitors, comes at a crucial time for the Gooda
Walker Names Action Group, which last month voted by a 5-1 majority to
pursue legal action rather than accept its share of a Pounds 900m
out-of-court settlement offer.
It is understood that the application was made after a potentially vital
witness was advised by his solicitors not to give evidence in the civil
action, while there is a pending investigation by the Serious Fraud Office
into the agency's affairs. News of the SFO probe, which focuses on the use
by Gooda Walker of so-called 'time and distance' reinsurance policies,
emerged last year.
Mr Philip Rocher of Wilde Sapte, the solicitors working with the action
group, said Names would 'strenuously resist' the adjournment application,
which is to be heard on Friday or early next week.
An adjournment would be a blow to Gooda Names because their legal action -
one of the biggest being fought by Names - was one of the first Names'
actions scheduled to come to court. Gooda Names are therefore hoping to have
greater access to the limited pool of errors-and-omissions insurance cover -
which protects agents against negligence awards - than some other
lossmakers.
Insurance market leaders have said that 70 per cent of Names - by value of
the offer - must accept if it is to go ahead. But it appears that Lloyd's
will be unable to persuade enough Names to accept the deal before a deadline
of February 14.
The implementation later this year in the UK of the European Union's third
non-life directive will tighten the solvency regulations faced by UK
insurers and could add to pressures faced by some smaller reinsurers in the
London market, according to Price Waterhouse, the accountants. Under the new
regulations insurers and reinsurers will no longer be able to count premiums
and reinsurance recoveries which are more than three months overdue as
assets for solvency purposes.
</TEXT>
