<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / BR memos reveal concern over contractor training
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Rail managers have serious concerns about gaps in the training of
staff of private railway contractors, it emerged in BR documents leaked
yesterday.
The letters, obtained by Mr Brian Wilson, a Labour transport spokesman,
reveal what he called 'an alarming level of concern about safety in the
run-up to privatisation'.
In one memo to British Rail managers, MrChris Dickinson, BR's head of safety
audit, warns: 'Many contractors undertaking safety training of would-be
on-track staff have no knowledge of the standardsinvolved and have no
mechanism to obtain them officially.
'The onus should be on the contractor to prove he understands what standards
are required andhow he has trained his staff as part of the contractor
appraisal system.'
Mr Wilson said: 'The clear message is that people with no previous railway
experience are being let loose without adequate checks or training. This is
part of the privatisation process. It must be stopped.'
British Rail confirmed that the documents were genuine but said they merely
showed that the organisation was concerned that contractors' staff must be
properly trained.
In a second document obtained by Mr Wilson, Mr Robert Bartlett, training
manager for InterCity, wrote: 'My concern is the safety of all staff, be it
contractor or BR, who are working on or near the line on the railway. If
these persons receive inaccurate or inadequate training then this could lead
to unnecessary and unacceptable accidents.'
Mr Wilson said the disclosure of these concerns by BRmanagers came shortly
after an incident near Derby, when a privately owned maintenance train
travelled 30 miles in the wrong direction. He added: 'A fragmented railway
is a less safe railway. If private companies employ staff who are
inexperienced and under-trained, then there are going to be incidents and
accidents.'
Railtrack, the company formed to own and manage BR's track, signalling and
stations, will today announce details of a campaign to sign up contractors
and suppliers to the privatised network.
</TEXT>
