FT  02 FEB 94 / Labour council proposes tax cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Birmingham's Labour-controlled city council, the largest metropolitan
authority in Britain, yesterday proposed a cut in the council tax for
1994-95 and contrasted its revenue demands with the government's
introduction of VAT increases.
The cut, of Pounds 17 to Pounds 421 a year in the lowest property valuation
bandand of Pounds 50 to Pounds 1264 a year in the highest band, comes
despite an unsuccessfulattempt by the council to win extra government
funding and before May electionswhere if Labour loses four seats, it loses
control.
The council's total budget for 1994-95 is provisionally set at Pounds
938.86m, compared with the 1992-93 budget of Pounds 901.47m.
In response to criticism that too much has been spent on prestige projects
like the International Convention Centre and not enough on education, the
council is lifting the education budget by Pounds 40.1m to Pounds 448.3m. Of
this total, Pounds 9.6m would be on the capital account - more than double
the 1992-93 budget. On the revenue side there would be an increase of Pounds
30.5m.
