FT  02 FEB 94 / World Trade News: US plans crackdown over financial services
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHI NGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Clinton administration yesterday said the open US financial services
market should no longer be 'free' to countries which do not give 'fair
treatment' to US banking and securities firms overseas.
Mr Rufus Yerxa, deputy US trade representative, told a House banking
subcommittee the administration would support the proposed Fair Trade in
Financial Services Act and use it to supplement efforts to open markets in
the Uruguay Round and the Japan negotiating framework talks.
'The US does not intend to target under this legislation existing operations
of foreign companies established within the US,' he said. 'We believe that
any policy should be focused on limiting access to new firms or new
opportunities.'
An opening of the Japanese huge financial services markets is of particular
importance to the expansion and global competitiveness of US firms.
The administration wants the treasury secretary to be able to grant market
access to individual companies. The act will be used to complement US
multilateral, bilateral and regional efforts to gain access to foreign
markets on equal terms with domestic firms.
</TEXT>
