<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / Greenspan warns on derivatives
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Central banks must work together to reduce the risk that financial systems
will collapse as result of upsets in the trading of financial derivatives,
Mr Alan Greenspan, Federal Reserve chairman, warned last night.
Mr Greenspan, who argued that central banks should retain responsibility for
banking supervision as well as monetary policy, said derivatives trading by
international banks posed challenges to the stability of financial systems.
Derivatives - financial contracts whose value depends on underlying
instruments such as currency exchange or interest rates - had helped to
heighten the inter-dependence of financial markets and market participants.
'Disturbances in one country or sector are rapidly transmitted throughout
the world economy. They pose challenges to central banks'. . .
responsibility for the stability of the world's interdependent financial
systems,' he said.
Mr Greenspan, addressing the Bankers Club in London, said co-ordination
among central banks had become essential because problems in financial
markets were increasingly likely to have systemic consequences crossing
borders.
His remarks are the latest expression of concern by an international bank
supervisor at the potential risks created by derivatives, which are
predominantly used by companies and financial institutions to hedge risks.
The Fed chairman emphasised that the growth of derivatives reinforced
central banks' mandate 'whether written in law or not' to protect the
integrity of financial systems, as well as overseeing monetary policy and
payment systems.
Last year Mr Greenspan attacked US Treasury plans to consolidate banking
supervision, currently spread among four agencies, including the Fed, into a
single Federal Banking Commission. The Fed would retain its responsibilities
for monetary policy and the payments system under the proposals.
The solving of financial crises often depended on central banks having a
dual role, even if this was de facto, he said yesterday.
'The successful resolution of financial crises often depends upon links
between the insights and expertise gained through banking supervision, and
those gained from the pursuit of macroeconomic stability.'
The development of derivatives and risk management had 'yielded great
benefits' to financial institutions and their customers, but had generated
'an elaborate web of financial interrelationships'.
He said that difficulties at internationally active banks 'could well have
an impact on a wide range of other financial institutions, and through them
on the economy'.
Mr Greenspan said the Fed and other central banks had worked with banks 'to
seek in advance improvements that could mitigate the potential for systemic
disruption without destroying the benefits of these useful instruments'.
</TEXT>
