<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / IMF warning on further Russian loans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The International Monetary Fund yesterday promised that its mission to
Moscow would be open-minded in economic policy talks with the government,
but warned that it would not be easy to agree to further loans.
Mr Michel Camdessus, IMF managing director, said the mission, which began
work yesterday and is expected to remain in Moscow for two to three weeks,
would listen to the plans of Mr Victor Chernomyrdin's government, and would
'try to be helpful'.
However, the IMF's willingness to release the next Dollars 1.5bn loan for
which Russia could qualify under the fund's special facility for former
Communist countries was 'not a foregone conclusion,' he said.
From what the IMF had heard so far, the new government appeared to be
diverging from the reform path agreed with the previous one.
Mr Camdessus warned that efforts to reduce inflation and stabilise the
rouble would not succeed for long without strong monetary and budget
policies, but he refused to dismiss out of hand Mr Chernomyrdin's suggestion
that the Russian government would try non-monetary ways of controlling
inflation. 'If it means they will be stronger in bringing down the budget
deficit, this is music to our ears.'
But IMF officials said they were concerned that the new government appeared
to be ready to let its inflation target slip back to 18 per cent a month by
the end of 1994, compared with a rate of 12 per cent in December.
They acknowledged, however, that the latter rate had been achieved in part
by limiting the government's borrowing from the central bank by not paying
its bills. Some of the accumulated arrears would have to be paid in the
first quarter, probably bringing inflation back to a monthly rate of near 20
per cent, said the head of the IMF's Russia department.
Mr Camdessus fiercely defended the fund against charges of being too
insensitive in its dealings with Russia or too strict in the conditions it
imposed. 'We are the scapegoat,' he complained, insisting that if the
international community wanted to give unconditional aid to Russia, the
money should come from bilateral grants.
He acknowledged that the IMF had only lent a total of Dollars 2.5bn to
Russia so far, rather than the Dollars 14bn announced in separate packages
by the Group of Seven leading industrial countries. 'We were unable to
disburse more because we must respect our rules,' he said.
He pointed out that western donors had delivered Dollars 20bn of the Dollars
21bn promised by the G7, and that official and commercial debt rescheduling,
as well as money provided by Germany to rehouse Russian troops, brought the
total of external financial assistance to Dollars 58bn.
Personal view, Page 19
</TEXT>
