<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / End to airline subsidies urged: State-owned airlines must
prepare for privatisation, say 'wise men'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER, RACHEL JOHNSON and JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, LONDON, PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
State-owned airlines in Europe can no longer expect to be drip-fed on
subsidies and must prepare for eventual privatisation, according to a report
sponsored by the European Commission.
The report, by an independent committee of 'wise men' representing the
European airline industry, rejected any rolling back of the limited
deregulation already under way.
But the committee softened its deregulatory message by offering European
Union states the chance to give a 'one time, last time' dose of aid to
support restructuring in an industry that lost Dollars 700m (Pounds 466m) in
1992. Mr Hermann De Croo, a former Belgian transport minister and the
committee chairman, came out in favour of privatisation as the 'ultimate
solution', but suggested that one last shot of state aid might be needed to
put the industry back on its feet. A sick patient could not be expected to
come off a drip immediately before starting to walk again, he said.
Those seeking to extend the 'open skies' regime welcomed the report, which
was published yesterday, even though the committee had stopped short of
recommending an outright ban on state aid.
Mr John MacGregor, the UK transport secretary, said the recommendations on
extending liberalisation and generally eliminating state aid were a 'ringing
endorsement' of British competition policy.
The UK aviation industry - which, unlike some of its competitors, has to
compete without state subsidy - was predictably more enthusiastic than that
of Europe's troubled state carriers.
British Airways - which only last month called on the European Commission to
force Air France to repay a FFr1.5bn (Pounds 170m) capital injection from
the French government - called the report a 'victory for the consumer and
for competition'. British Midland called it a 'great step forward.'
State-owned Air France and Alitalia were not ready to offer comment, but
both are thought unlikely to welcome the findings.
Air France has resisted rapid deregulation of the European airline industry,
and is seeking a further FFr5bn state aid as it undergoes restructuring.
Belgium's Sabena said the document was 'interesting' because it offered so
many concrete recommendations.
Because the panel's recommendations are non-binding, much will depend on
political will to implement its findings. That will be tested when
state-owned airlines request additional state aid.
The Commission has already opened infringement proceedings against Air
France, which last year faced French government opposition to its own
efforts to shed labour and stem heavy losses. Other possible state aid
applicants include Alitalia, Olympic Airways of Greece, Sabena, and Iberia
of Spain.
Mr De Croo said in Brussels yesterday that the panel had sought to strike a
balance in the debate between liberalisation and protection, but he added:
'There is no solution to save this sector by going back to the past.'
The committee also recommended that, within the next six months, governments
should set a deadline of June 1995 to establish a common external aviation
policy under the Treaty of Rome.
'Wise men' see turbulence on the horizon, Page 2
Editorial Comment, Page 19
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
