<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / Major rebuffs Tory right on cabinet changes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major threw out right-wing demands for changes in his cabinet
line-up yesterday in a move calculated to restore some of his authority over
the government.
However, the government's difficulties continued to mount as Mr Michael
Howard, home secretary, prepared for a retreat today on the controversial
police bill and Mr Kenneth Clarke, chancellor, admitted that senior
ministers were 'beleaguered'.
It also emerged that the cabinet will rush through approval tomorrow for
reports from five pay review bodies giving 1.5m public sector workers pay
rises of between 2.5 per cent and 3 per cent.
Downing Street is understood to be 'relaxed' about the reports, which will
be funded by efficiency savings to circumvent the cash freeze on the
government's pay bill announced in the budget.
Buttressed by support from mainstream Conservative MPs, Mr Major left little
doubt about his anger at the Tory right's demands.
A delegation of MPs from the right-wing 92 Group emerged chastened from Mr
Major's Commons office a few minutes after arriving to demand urgent
changes. The prime minister was particularly angry about publicity given to
the meeting, which suggested that he was being offered terms for his
survival as leader.
Friends of Mr Major said the talks broke up only two minutes after the
arrival of the deputation, led by Sir George Gardiner, the 92 Group
chairman.
The right put a brave face on its defeat, insisting that the meeting lasted
nearly 10 minutes, and claiming it had been 'deferred' by agreement with Mr
Major. 'We did not feel it was a brush off by the prime minister,' Sir
George said.
However, Mr Major's robust response was applauded by centrist and left-wing
supporters. 'This was the prime minister exercising a firm grip on
government,' said one. It was also welcomed by right-wing MPs who believe
that the government's difficulties are rooted in the prime minister's
failure to exercise authority over the Conservative party.
'We have seen another side of the prime minister,' said Mr David Evans, an
independent-minded right-wing member of the executive of the 1922 Committee
of Tory backbenchers.
Mr Major's robust action will quell speculation about an early reshuffle,
which most MPs now believe will be delayed until after the local government
and European parliament elections in May and June.
It will also seriously undermine the influence of Sir George, who was widely
regarded as a right-wing power broker until he lost his place on the 1922
executive last year.
Conservative MPs were heartened by Mr Major's unusually aggressive
performance during Commons question time, when he angrily dismissed
criticism of the sale of Rover to BMW from Mr John Smith, the Labour leader.
However, senior ministers admit that the government still has a lot to do to
restore its authority. Mr Clarke said on BBC radio that the prime minister
was 'getting criticised very unfairly at the moment'.
Howard yields to critics, Page 7
</TEXT>
