<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / London Stock Exchange: Futures selling wipes out initial
market gains - Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Another powerful early showing by the UK stock marketdrove the FT-SE 100
Index to yet another all-time intraday peak. But it ran outof steam in
midsession when the Footsie future turned sharply lower and, later,Wall
Street succumbed to a bout of profit-taking.
The FT-SE 100 was, however, sprinkled with some big winners, with British
Aerospace turning in anothersparkling performance as the City continued to
register its approval of BMW's purchase of the Rover car manufacturer.
There was also said to have been another significant shift from the FT-SE
100 constituents and into the FT-SE Mid 250 stocks after the recent bout of
underperformance by the latter. Dealers saidmany of the big securities
houses, which have been lining up covered warrants against the second-line
stocks, had moved in to cover short positions on their trading books. The
London International Financial Futures and Options Exchange is launching its
FT-SE Mid 250 Index futures contract on February 25.
The sell-off in equities was said to have been triggered largely by an
abrupt turnround in international bond markets and talk of a big seller in
the Footsie future.
Share prices moved ahead strongly at the outset, with the FT-SE 100
Indexreaching an all-time peak of 3,514.3 within an hour of the opening as
the cash market responded to Wall Street's overnight advance to record
levels and the further rise by the Tokyo equity market.
The market suddenly came under pressure, however, as the appearance of a big
seller saw the FT-SE future dive and trade at a discount to the cash market
for much of the rest of the session. What disconcerted other traders in the
Liffe market was that the big seller had only minutes earlier been an
aggressive buyer of the future.
Gilt-edged stocksalso played a big part in the market's retreat. News of the
resignation of the deputy chairman of the Federal Reserve was said to have
unnerved US bonds, whichin turn brought substantial downward pressure to
bear on UK gilts.
At its worst, the FT-SE 100 showed a loss of 20.8 points, before stabilising
in the last hour of the trading session as the second-line stocks continued
to climb.
The FT-SE 100 finished 10.3 off on the day at 3,481.5, while the FT-SE Mid
Cap settled 21.1 higher at 4,105.4. Turnover was a heavy 1.087bn shares,
marginally ahead of Monday's 1.084bn, with activity in second liners
accounting for 699.3m shares, or 64 per cent of the total. The Stock
Exchange said the value of customer business transacted in the market on
Monday was Pounds 1.76bn, below levels reached last week but still well
above usual daily amounts for January.
The mo tor component stocks were said to have attracted extremely heavy
demand and to have played a big part in the strong showing by the Mid 250
Index.
HSBC Holdings was the focus of attention in a busy banks area, with the
shares sprinting ahead amid hints that one of the big securities houses  -
BZW was mentioned - could be about to issue a covered warrant against the
shares. Life stocks were boosted by suggestions of an imminent buy
recommendation for companies such asLloyds Abbey and Legal &amp; General.
The relisting of Berisford saw the shares rocket as the market displayed its
pleasure with the terms of its acquisition of the Magnet business.
</TEXT>
