<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Fading hopes of a reduction in German interest rates this week, together
with active selling from leading securities houses, brought a retreat by
stock index futures, writes Joel Kibazo.
Dealers reported an erratic start to the session after the first trade in
the March contract on the FT-SE 100 was struck at 3,512.
The early activity included what initially appeared to be a big buy order,
sending the contract advancing to 3,524. The realisation that it was an
order to sell saw March reverse earlier gains.
A feeling that tomorrow's Bundesbank meeting was unlikely toannounce a
reduction in German rates, weakness in the gilts sector and selling from
some of the big brokers, only served to increase the slide.
After a further retreat in the afternoon brought about by a dull opening on
Wall Street,dealers were suddenly caught short, which led to a squeeze just
ahead of the official close.
March, which traded at a discount to cash for much of the session, ended at
3,481, seven points below its previous close and just ahead of its fair
value premium of about one point. Volume at the official close stood
at15,380 contracts.
In traded options, turnover in the FT-SE 100 option improved to 15,034,
making a significant contribution to the day's total of 43,657 lots.
However, the Euro-FT-SE 100 option performance was below its recent average
and traded a mere 1,533 contracts.
SmithKline Beecham was the most actively dealt stock option, closing with
4,156 contracts, followed by Hanson at 3,334 trades.
</TEXT>
