<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / World Stock Markets: Equity hopes raised by Lebanon
reawakening - Mark Nicholson hears talk of a bonanza in Beirut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARK NICHOLSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If investments of cash come to match those ofhope in Lebanon's reawakening
capital market, there is a bonanza in store.
Blakeney Management, London-based specialists in Middle East markets, tells
clients in its first-quarter bulletin that 'Beirut has the potential to be
one of the best-performing markets this year'.
Merrill Lynch advised its emerging market watchers late in 1993 that Lebanon
was, with Cuba, Vietnam and Israel, a country where returning expatriate
capital could ignite the local financialmarket.
Mr Riad Salame, governor of Lebanon's central bank, quotes IFC data
forecasting that Lebanon's equity market could reach a capitalisation of
Dollars 25bn within a decade.
Meanwhile, it is early days. Although Lebanon has been at peace for more
than three years and reconstruction is gathering pace, the country's capital
market is presently little more than a twinkle in investors' eyes.
Beirut's stock market has been closed since the middle of the civil war and
the sole negotiable securities at present are Lebanese pound denomination
government treasury bills.
But there are signs of movement. The first was the successful share offering
last month to capitalise Solidere, the Dollars 1.8bn company which will
manage the reconstruction of downtown Beirut.
Mr Salamesays that a secondary market in the Dollars 100 shares should open
within a few weeks. In the absence of a stock market, he says, the shares
will be quoted and tradeable under the auspices of the Societe Financiere du
Liban, a group jointly ownedby 44 of Lebanon's commercial banks, which will
at the same time centralise allT-Bill trading.
In time, and Mr Salame is reluctant to say how much time, this centralised
market will form the basis for a reopened stock and bond exchange.
Much needs to be done first, including making amendments to capital market
legislation and finding a new building for a fully fledged exchange. But,
with an eye on growing emerging market funds available from London, New York
andelsewhere, Mr Salame says that the market, when it reopens, will be open
to direct foreign investment. 'We have always been an open market, and we
intend to remain such,' he adds.
A number of foreign institutions are, accordingly,starting to position
themselves.
Both Paribas, the French merchant bank, and Saudi American Bank, the Saudi
joint-venture bank - both of which acted as subscription agents in the
Solidere issue - are understood to be setting up localbranches shortly.
Paribas is considering establishing a separate investment company. Merrill
Lynch is also said to be looking to expand its small Beirutoffice; and
Banque Audi, the Beirut-based commercial bank, says it expects thisyear to
establish the first local investment fund.
</TEXT>
<XX>
