<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / World Stock Markets (Asia Pacific): Hong Kong up 3% as Tokyo
volume climbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Monday's sharp rise attracted active trading, and the Nikkei average closed
moderately higher as volume jumped to 950m shares, writes Emiko Terazono in
Tokyo.
The 225-issue index gained 187.22 at 20,416.34 as corporate investors sold
into strength, supported by buying by overseas investors and domestic
individuals. The Topix index of all first section stocks added 13.88 at
1,643.10, but inLondon the ISE/Nikkei 50 index retreated 12.61 to 1,346.17.
The Nikkei fell to the day's low of 20,237.52 in the morning, and peaked at
20,509.95 inthe afternoon, rising above 20,500 for the first time since
October 26 last year. Selling pressure from institutional investors, who had
bought shares in orderto support the Nikkei index last year, was especially
strong at those levels.
Traders said the Nikkei's recovery past the 20,000 level had boosted
investor confidence. 'Monday's rise was more effective in supporting the
market than an income tax cut, since it increased the Tokyo market's
capitalisation by Y20,000bn,' said Mr Yasuo Ueki at Nikko Securities.
Buying ahead of Thursday's announcement of the government's economic
stimulus package may drive the index above the next resistance line of
21,148 reached in September.
Nippon Telegraph and Telephone put on Y32,000 at Y1.01m, recovering the Y1m
level for the first time since April 19 last year. Other telecommunication
and multimedia related issues were also higher, with Fujitsu rising Y20 to
Y1,040 and Fujikura, a cable maker, gaining Y21 at Y1,010.
The yen's strengthening hurtexport-oriented sectors. Pioneer Electronic fell
Y40 to Y2,980 and Hitachi declined Y3 to Y902. Steelmakers were weak, with
Kawasaki Steel slipping Y9 to Y372.
Honda Motor receded Y40 to Y1,700 following BMW's acquisition of Rover.
Some banks were lower on profit-taking. Industrial Bank of Japanshed Y20 to
Y3,340.
In Osaka, the OSE average added 256.82 at 22,121.65 in volume of 83.8m
shares. Roundup
The region was mainly stronger on renewed foreign demand for equity. Kuala
Lumpur was closed.
HONG KONG rose sharply on overseas buying ahead of the Chinese new year,
encouraged by approval of a funding plan for the new airport.
The Hang Seng index advanced 339.87, or nearly 3 per cent, to 11,826.89.
Turnover expanded to HKDollars 9.2bn from Monday's HKDollars 7.1bn.
Expectations of strong corporate results aided sentiment, brokers added.
Among the blue chips, HSBC Holdings topped the active list, surging
HKDollars 5 to HKDollars 120, while Hang Seng Bank rose HKDollars 1.50 to
HKDollars 77. Cheung Kong put onHKDollars 2 at HKDollars 50.50.
SEOUL climbed to finish at a 52-month high in spite of selling pressure from
the market stabilisation fund, which placed sell orders worth Won400bn.
The composite index moved up 14.39, or 1.52 per cent, to 960.10. Turnover
amounted to Won1,350bn.
TAIWAN was supported by buying of stocks in the construction sector, which
has lagged behind the market's recent rise. The weighted index ended 61.79
higher at 6,176.91 in turnover of TDollars 101bn, after Monday's TDollars
89.25bn.
Textile stocks remained firm on expectations of a recovery in the industry
and higher product prices. Shinkong Synthetic Fibres moved forward TDollars
1.20 to TDollars 30.20.
MANILA slipped back following worries over bomb attacks on three oil
companies and fears of further protests against a 15 per cent increase in
fuel prices.
The composite index surrendered 39.07to 2,835.49 in turnover of 1.14bn
pesos.
SINGAPORE was firmer, helped by foreign demand for selected stocks. The
Straits Times Industrial index rose 9.98 to 2,349.08.
NEW ZEALAND gained fresh impetus from economic data which showed an
improvement in growth. The NZSE-40 capital index added 25.7 at 2,423.62.
Telecom, which has been leading the market higher in recent sessions,
advanced a further 11 cents to NZDollars 4.96.
PAKISTAN rose on the first day of the new account and the KSE 100 index
closed 28.00 stronger at 2,272.07.
Brokers said they expected share prices to continue to recover after heavy
selling pressure last week.
