<TEXT>
London Metal Exchange ALUMINIUM prices continued to benefit yesterday from
the positive sentiment fostered by the draft agreement on cutting global
production. Speculative investment fund buying lifted the three-months price
to Dollars 1,265 a tonne, a Dollars 33 gain from Monday, with the rise also
fuelled by fresh buying of March and April Dollars 1,300 call options.
The COPPER market, although remaining nervous about the implications of huge
losses in futures trading suffered by Codelco, the Chilean state producer,
was some Dollars 20 higher in the three months position and trying to erode
chart-based resistance around Dollars 1,890 a tonne.
The London GOLD was again led higher by SILVER, which gained 17 cents to
Dollars 5.21 1/2 cents a troy ounce and looked like testing resistance at
Dollars 5.25, traders said. The yellow metal closed at Dollars 384.75 an
ounce, up Dollars 6.50 on the day.
