<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: Kazakhstan aims to boost gold
output by at least 200 per cent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Kazakhstan, formerly part of the Soviet Union, expects a substantial
increase in gold output over the next three or four years, according to Mr
Abdrakhman Begalinov, president of Altynalmas, the organisation responsible
for the republic's precious metals and precious stones production.
Last year the republic produced about 14 tonnes of gold, he says, and the
government wants this lifted to between 42 and 56 tonnes very quickly to
build reserves to back the country's new currency.
Mr Begalinov admits that Kazakhstan will have difficulty raising funds for
such a fast expansion but he has high hopes of attracting more foreign
investors. At present Altynalmas, which encompasses 21 enterprises employing
5,000 people. is discussing specific projects with more than 10 foreign
mining companies, he says.
Kazakhstan's need to build gold reserves means that, during its transition
to a market economy, all gold must be sold to the government - which also
insists on keeping majority control of each joint venture. However, Mr
Begalinov says the central bank will pay in US dollars for the gold at the
world market price.
He says Kazakhstan faces a huge task of reconstruction and its mining
industry, which has a long tradition and is well-developed, will play a very
important role. The country is very rich in minerals - more than 60
different minerals are produced - and the republic accounted for more than
half of all the lead, zinc and copper produced by the Soviet Union.
Mr Begalinov is in London for discussions with Bakyrchik Gold, the
London-quoted company involved in one of Kazakhstan's biggest gold projects.
The UK company has 40 per cent of a joint venture with Altynalmas to develop
the Bakyrchik mine, located in an arid region of the north-eastern steppes
of Kazakhstan. The mine is on one of the world's biggest gold deposits,
containing about 8m troy ounces, but the ore is very complex and difficult
to process.
Mr Bill Hussey, Bakyrchik's operations director, says that the partnership
is on schedule to lift gold production to an annual rate of 36,000 troy
ounces by June. It has yet to be decided when Bakyrchik will approach its
300 shareholders - many of them blue-chip institutions - for part of the
Pounds 75m needed for a second phase to lift output to 250,000 ounces.
Meanwhile, 'our relationship with the local people is getting stronger every
day'.
</TEXT>
