<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / Commodities and Agriculture: African producers set cobalt
'reference' price
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The sharp rise in the free market price of cobalt - it has doubled since
December to about Dollars 22 a pound - has caused Zambia and Zaire, the two
biggest western producers, to back away from setting a producer price for
the metal. Instead they have set a 'reference' price of Dollars 18 for the
next three months. unchanged from their previous producer price.
Some traders suggested yesterday that consumers would be lucky to obtain
high-grade cobalt - a hard metal used in superalloys in such things as
cutting tools, high-strength magnets andjet engines, as a powder in
catalysts for the oil and man-made fibre industriesand in radial tyres - at
the reference price. The producers would probably charge a premium for
better-quality material, they said.
On the other hand, some consumers thought the recent sharp price rise had
more to do with trader 'hype' than any fundamental shortage of metal. 'The
traders were determined to push the price up to Dollars 30 before letting it
fall back,' said one.
However, statistics from the Cobalt Development Institute, whose members
produce about 97 per cent of western world cobalt, suggest the market was
about in balance last year. A fall from about 18,000 tonnes to 15,000 tonnes
in western cobalt production was probably compensated for by an increase in
imports from Russia and by stocks left over from late-1992 production.
Meanwhile, demand is estimated by the institute to have remained at about
19,000 tonnes.
This year, the CDI suggests, demand is likely to remain stable while western
production may fall again. Even if Russian exports remain at about 2,000
tonnes and the US authorities go ahead with the planned release of another
2,500 tonnes from their strategic stockpile, supply will do well to keep up
with demand.
</TEXT>
