<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / International Bonds: VW's DM500m issue likely to attract
investors on Continent
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MANILA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Volkswagen, the German car manufacturer, provided the highlight of the
international bond market yesterday with the launch of a DM500m five-year
Eurobond.
The issue from Volkswagen International Finance, which has an A1/AA- credit
rating, is expected to attract interest from continental European investors,
particularly in the retail sector where Volkswagen is a household name.
However, some market participants were surprised by the choice of
book-runner, CSFB, which succeeded in getting in ahead of the two German
joint leads - Deutsche Bank and Dresdner Bank. It is unusual for a
non-German house to act as book-runner in a deal for a German borrower, and
there was a fair amount of speculation in the market that CSFB had won the
mandate on the grounds of aggressive pricing.
The bonds, which have a 5 3/8 per cent coupon, were priced to yield 32 basis
points over the 5 per cent government bond due 1999. The deal will break
syndicate today.
The other main feature of the Eurobond market yesterday was the burst of
activity in the Swiss franc sector, where borrowers launched a flood of
mainly equity-linked deals.
With Swiss franc interest rates at their current low levels, specialists in
the sector point out that the only way to stimulate any investor interest is
with the addition of an equity kicker, either using a convertible bond
structure or by attaching warrants.
Among the other deals of the day, the Republic of Portugal's Ecu750m,
10-year issue was priced to yield 28 basis points over the 6 per cent Ecu
OAT due 2004. Morgan Stanley, one of the joint lead managers, said the bonds
were still trading at the issue price of 98.325 by late afternoon.
Meanwhile, the People's Republic of China is expected to launch its
long-awaited Dollars 1bn bond issue shortly, dealers said.
The Philippine central bank imposed limits on the amount that public and
private institutions will be allowed to raise in the international bond
market to prevent a recurrence of the debt crisis of the 1980s, Reuter
reports from Manila.
Mr Gabriel Singson, central bank governor, said the 1994 limit would be
Dollars 2.5bn for long-term bond issues and Dollars 300m for short-term
issues.
To keep within the target, Mr Singson said President Fidel Ramos had ordered
state agencies and corporations to have their borrowing plans approved by
the central bank before issuing bonds.
Moody's Investors Service, the credit rating agency, has raised the
subordinated debt rating of HSBC Holdings to A3 from Baa1. The rating for
long-term deposits for Midland Bank, the UK banking subsidiary of HSBC
Holdings, was also raised, to Aa3 from A1.
</TEXT>
