<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / International Capital Markets: Canada turns in top
performance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB and TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Canad a was the top performing government bond market last month, as a
combination oflow inflation, high unemployment and an easing in short-term
interest rates prompted a rally and provided investors with a return of 2.05
per cent in local currency terms.
'Investors' appetites for Canadian fixed-income securities have been whetted
by widespread expectations that Canadian bonds would continue to outperform
their US counterparts . . . these expectations have been reinforced by
better inflation performance and persistent high unemployment levels in
Canada, along with further gradual easing of short rates by the Bank of
Canada,' says J. P. Morgan Securities in its monthly report on government
bond performance.
Spanish government bonds ranked second with a return of 1.88 per cent in
January, helped by an improving inflation picture and a 25 basis point cut
in the Bank of Spain's intervention rate.
In general, the higher-yielding European government bond markets remained
firm at the start of the year, while thecore European government bond
markets showed only small gains, as market participants became less
optimistic about the prospects of a near-term easing by the Bundesbank.
Japan was the worst performing government bond market, showinga fall of 3.34
per cent in local currency terms. The strong performance of bond markets
last year boosted turnover on Euroclear, the world's largest international
securities clearing house, to a record Dollars 17,300bn, up 77 per cent on
1992, writes Tracy Corrigan.
Euroclear is expected to have increased its shareof the market with rival
Cedel to more than 70 per cent. Average daily turnoverrose from Dollars 37bn
to Dollars 66bn.
Euroclear gave rebates totalling Dollars 12m to the market, since it does
not retain profits except for further investment in development.
</TEXT>
