<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / International Company News: S African life assurer sells
subsidiary to black grouping
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MATTHEW CURTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Southern Life, one of South Africa's biggest life assurers, has sold a
controlling stake in subsidiary African Life to a consortium of prominent
black businessmen for R160m (Dollars 47m) in a significant move towards
black economic empowerment.
Control in African Life, which has assets of R313m, will pass to a new
company - it now has a working name of Newco - to be owned by the consortium
and a number of black organisations ranging from trade union federation
Cosatu to church groups, the National Association of Stokvels -
community-based savings organisations - and provident and pension funds.
This aspect of the deal sets it apart from earlier moves towardsblack
economic empowerment. Newly-formed black-owned companies, without such
diverse community shareholders, gained an important stake in Metropolitan
Life, a middle-ranking life assurer, and took control of the Sowetan, the
leading black newspaper, in the past year.
Mr Don Ncube, leader of the consortium and an alternate director of Anglo
American, which controls Southern Life, said African Life would be 'a mirror
of South African society' with Newco well-placed tobecome a vehicle for
foreign investment.
Newco would acquire 51 per centof African Life from Southern Life but the
company's management would remain inplace. The consortium had 120 days in
which to raise the money to conclude the deal but had commitments in
principle from the community and other groups to buyshares in Newco.
Mr Ncube said the acquisition was settled only after exhaustive talks with
community groups and Southern Life, and a due diligence study of African
Life by accountants Arthur Andersen, paid for by the Black Integrated
Commercial Support Network.
</TEXT>
