<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / International Company News: Cominco slides deeper into the
red
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Cominco, the Canadian base metals group, suffered another large loss last
year, but reported improvements in production and cost controls in the
fourth quarter.
The net loss, including gains on disposals, was CDollars 113.2m (USDollars
85.7m), or CDollars 1.46 a share, compared with CDollars 30.2m, or 42 cents,
in 1992. Revenues dipped to CDollars 982m from CDollars 1.47bn, due largely
to the spin-off of the fertiliser division.
While the operating loss for the year widened to CDollars 129m from CDollars
62.5m, it narrowed in the fourth quarter to CDollars 4.4m from CDollars
43.7m. The last figure included a CDollars 30m inventory write-down, but
metal prices last year were below 1992.
Cominco said output of its Red Dog zinc mine in Alaska climbed by 63 per
cent in the fourth quarter to 126,000 tonnes of concentrate. Two mills came
on stream in mid-January, and improvements in production and ore yields were
expected this year.
The troubled Trail smelter in British Columbia broke even on an operating
basis in the final three months, in spite of the slide in metal prices. The
smelter's lead and zinc output last year was about 95 per cent of 1993
levels. The Quebrada Blanca project in Chile is to produce cathode copper in
the second quarter of 1994.
