FT  02 FEB 94 / International Company News: Sextant, Allied Signal abandon
plans for link
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Sextant Avionique of France and Allied Signal of the US yesterday announced
that they had abandoned plans to form a joint venture in avionics which
would have created one of the world's largest aircraft electronics groups.
The companies said they were 'well positioned in their markets but that they
were unable to find a mutually satisfactory way to integrate Allied Signal's
commercial avionics and Sextant's commercial and military avionics
businesses in a satisfactory way'.
The problem appeared to involve Sextant's desire to guarantee the
confidentiality of its defence-related activities. Sextant, which is
controlled by Thomson-CSF, the French state-owned defence and civil
electronics group, derives just under half of its sales from military
activities.
When Sextant announced last year that it was negotiating to form a joint
venture with Allied, the French company estimated that combined sales could
total more than FFr1bn (Dollars 170m).
In spite of the failure of the joint venture, the two companies said that
they would continue to explore areas of co-operation in the commercial
avionics market.
