</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Molson, the international brewing and retailing group, said third-quarter
profits held up well and most sectors turned in better performances.
Net income was flat at CDollars 25.4m (USDollars 19.2m), or 43 cents a
share, against CDollars 25.3m, or 42 cents, a year earlier on revenues of
CDollars 748m, against CDollars 770m.
Nine-month earnings were CDollars 99.3m, or CDollars 1.68, against CDollars
100.1m, or CDollars 1.68, on revenues of CDollars 1.83bn against CDollars
1.85bn.
A 20 per cent stake in Molson Breweries, a subsidiary, was sold to Miller of
the US last April. This saw Molson's share of the brewing results fall to 40
per cent from 50 per cent. Its share of brewing profits in the nine months
dipped 25 per cent to CDollars 102m.
Beer exports to the US were up 22 per cent, mainly due to successful new
products.
New beers were introduced in Canada, the UK and Australia, although domestic
market share slipped slightly.
Diversey, the special chemicals unit, improved sales and operating profit in
North America, Europe, Japan and Latin America, but suffered from currency
fluctuations. Profitability still lags in the US cleaning business.
The Malsham hardware retailing unit forged ahead in Canada with volume up 16
per cent and higher operating profit. Sports and entertainment improved
profits sharply, mainly because of special factors.
