<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / International Company News: Partnership with Intel is
updated
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Intel and IBM have updated their long-standing technology partnership which
established Intel microprocessors as the standard for personal computers,
writes Louise Kehoe.
Under the new agreement, IBM will expand its own production of
Intel-designed 486 microprocessors, the 'brains' of most PCs. However, IBM
has elected not to manufacture Pentium, Intel's latest microprocessor.
The companies also extended a patent cross-licensing agreement that expired
last year.
Intel will pay an undisclosed 'non-material' sum to IBM 'to regain exclusive
manufacturing rights for Pentium and subsequent microprocessors,' Intel
said.
IBM's decision not to make the Pentium chip raises questions about its
commitment to the Intel microprocessor technology. IBM is about to launch a
new generation of computers based on PowerPC microprocessors, co-developed
with Motorola and Apple Computer.
'There is no question that PowerPC will compete directly with Pentium,'
acknowledged Mr James Cannavino, IBM senior vice-president.
However, he stressed that IBM plans to continue to develop products based on
Intel chips and said the timing of the announcement, coming shortly before
the expected introduction of PowerPC computers, was coincidental.
Intel is 'a vital IBM partner and supplier of technologies that fuel a
significant part of IBM's business,' said Mr Cannavino. 'We have a very
large and growing business in Intel-based computers.'
Mr Cannavino said IBM would have had to invest 'hundreds of millions of
dollars' in new production technology to produce the Pentium chip.
</TEXT>
