<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / International Company News: Euro Disney banks call meeting
on rescue deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Euro Disney's creditor banks will meet today in Paris for a special summit
meeting to map out their strategy for the final stage ofnegotiations over a
financial rescue package for the ailing leisure group.
The banks, which include J. P. Morgan, Deutsche Bank and National
Westminster, had originally hoped at the meeting to discuss an investigative
audit of Euro Disney that they have commissioned from KPMG Peat Marwick, the
accountancy company.
However, KPMG has been unable to finalise its audit allegedly becauseof Euro
Disney's reluctance to release information. It has instead prepared a
preliminary report. The final audit is scheduled for completion in two
weeks.
The banks have asked KPMG to analyse Euro Disney's financial position and
its future requirements to verify information given to them by Disney at a
meetingin November. Banking sources suggest that so far KPMG's findings do
not differ greatly from the Disney figures.
This means that the banks are likely to press for a swift resumption of
negotiations with Disney.
The US group has already tabled proposals to halve Euro Disney's FFr20.3bn
(Dollars 3.4bn) debt by raising FFr10bn through a rights issue and
debt-for-equity swap.
However, the banks are keen that Disney should share the burden of the
rescue. They will today discuss plans to reduce its entitlement to royalties
from Euro Disney and possibly to inject capital by purchasing assets. The
banks will also be briefed ontheir legal position by Gide-Loyrette-Nouelle,
their lawyers.
Meanwhile Adam, a French pressure group that represents minority
shareholders, is lobbyingfor the convertible bond holders (who hold FFr4bn
of Euro Disney's debt) to seethe KPMG report and to be represented in the
negotiations.
The talks could be further complicated by continuing sales of Euro Disney
debt on the US second-hand loans market. Midland Bank last month sold a
FFr130m portion of debt for60 per cent of its original value and a second
sale is now nearing completion.
Another sale, planned for last week, collapsed at the eleventh hour
following a dispute over the entitlement to voting rights.
</TEXT>
