<DATE>940202
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / International Equity Issues: No change in prospects for
conversion in Taiwan - The government is divided over the pace and scope of
financial liberalisation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
More than four years after Yuen Foong Yu Paper became the first Taiwanese
company to tap the Euromarket in convertible bonds - via a Dollars 100m,
10-year issue - prospects for conversion into equity appear as dim as ever.
This has not dissuaded international investors, keen for any sort of
exposure to Taiwan's fast-growing economy.
So difficult is it to buy into Taiwan'sequity market that even the vaguest
promises of direct access is enough to tempt fund managers.
Neither has it kept Taiwan companies from raising convertible debt.
Since YFY's issue in 1989, local companies have issued Dollars 515m and
SFr210m in 'convertible' Eurobonds. Three Euroconvertible issues were
launched in last month alone. At least 10 other companies have applications
pending.
Last October, Taiwan's central bank agreed to allow the conversion of
convertible bonds issued overseas, provided the cabinet approved the plan.
Themeasure was also subject to the US Securities and Exchange Commission's
revision of regulations related to overseas issuance of corporate bonds.
Analysts say that given the web of controls surrounding foreign investment
in Taiwan's stock market, the subject of convertibility poses a myriad trick
questions for regulators.
To begin with, only foreign institutional investors (FIIs) approved by the
central bank may invest directly in local shares: foreign individuals are
not allowed to buy Taiwan shares. As Euroconvertibles are traded
over-the-counter in the Eurobond market, the central bank has no control
over who owns them.
The central bank's October statement suggested that bonds held by foreign
individuals could be converted into global depository receipts.
However, todate just four Taiwan firms have issued GDRs, certificates listed
on overseas stock exchanges equivalent to shares in the issuing company.
None of the Euroconvertible issuers has done so.
Conversion also comes into conflict with restrictions on foreign ownership
of local shares.
The government imposes an overall ceiling of Dollars 5bn on total foreign
funds which may be brought into the country to invest in Taiwan shares.
There is also a Dollars 200m ceiling per approved FII, a limit of 10 per
cent on total foreign ownership in the shares in issue of a particular stock
and a 5 per cent limit on ownership by any individual FII.
Deep discord within the government over the pace and scope of financial
liberalisation ensures that in spite longstanding promises to loosen
significantly restrictions on foreign investment in Taiwan's bourse, in line
with plans to join the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, such measures
are unlikely to happen soon.
Meanwhile, investors can either hold bonds for the fixed return or profit by
trading them. Taiwan share prices are currently viewed as undervalued
relative to other regional equity markets.
For issuers, Euroconvertibles represent cheaper financing than they could
obtain at home. Last month's issues carried coupons of 2 per cent, compared
with rates of around 8 per cent in the domestic market. Taiwan's lack of an
established rating system for corporatedebt has made it difficult for all
but big companies to raise funds locally.
This appears to be a concern for investors in Taiwanese Euroconvertibles, in
spite of the fact that the local companies are largely unknown quantities
abroad.
Even medium-sized companies are considering issuing overseas - especially in
Switzerland, where rates and costs associated with issuance are lowest.
Given the plethora of issues set to enter the Eurobond markets and the
snail-like pace of reform, Taiwan's curious unconvertible convertible bonds
are likely to remain a fixture of the financial landscape for some time to
come.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>TWZ  Taiwan, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9311 Finance, Taxation, and Monetary Policy.
    P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 25
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT941-12000</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EBBDOAABFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940202
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 FEB 94 / International Company News: MIM details its plans for Musto
investment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MIM, the Australian metals group which is competing with Canada's Metall
Mining for the Bajo de la Alumbrera project in north-west Argentina,
yesterday released further details of its agreement with International Musto
Explorations, the small Canadian group whose main asset is the rich
Argentine copper-gold deposit.
MIM said that, of its proposed USDollars 130m payment to Musto for a50 per
cent interest in the project, Dollars 10m represents repayment of Musto's
investment in to date. The remainding Dollars 120m would cover Musto's
half-share of the costs of putting the mine into production.
Total development costs are put at Dollars 600m, but about Dollars 360m is
expected to come from project finance.
The deal between MIM and Musto comes on the heels of a hostile CDollars
232m(USDollars 175m) bid by Metall Mining, the international arm of
Germany's Metallgesellschaft, for Musto. This, however, is conditional on
Musto not signing a legally-binding joint venture agreement to dispose of a
substantial part of its 100 per cent interest in Alumbrera.
</TEXT>
