<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Mr Greenspan helps lift Dow
to new heights
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stocks again surged into record territory yesterday after remarks by the
Federal Reserve Board chairman reassured investors wary of inflation, writes
Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 32.93 ahead at 3,978.36, a third
consecutive all-time high. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 added 2.91 at 481.61,
while the American SE composite climbed 2.46 to 485.68 and the Nasdaq
composite advanced 3.94 to 800.47, surpassing the 800 mark for the first
time. Volume on the New York SE was heavy, with 322.9m shares changing
hands.
Stocks had several developments working in their favour. The powerful
advance staged by the Nikkei index overnight, after passage of a Japanese
political reform package, set an upbeat tone for the session's opening.
The positive sentiment was reinforced by Mr Alan Greenspan, Fed chairman,
who told a congressional committee that the central bank was committed to
stamping out inflationary pressures in the economy.
The vigilant tone of his remarks brought firmer prices to longer-dated US
Treasury bonds, which are particularly sensitive to inflation. In the
afternoon, however, the 30-year benchmark bond retraced its gains as
commodity prices rebounded, and ended the session in negative ground.
Higher commodity prices proved to be a favourable development for some
stocks. An agreement by the world's leading aluminium-producing countries to
cut global production gave a strong lift to the share prices of US suppliers
of the basic metal.
Alcoa, a component of the Dow Industrial index, surged Dollars 2 7/8 to
Dollars 79 1/8 , a 52-week high. Reynolds climbed Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars
53 3/8 , Alcan Aluminum Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 24 1/2 and Phelps Dodge
Dollars 1 to Dollars 54 1/4 .
The market received at least one piece of unwelcome news. The Purchasing
Management Association of Chicago revealed a modest downturn in its January
index of economic activity, possibly a preview of today's national survey.
In spite of the indication of a slowdown, stocks closely linked to broad
economic trends continued to gather strength. Investors showed particular
interest in automobile issues. General Motors rose Dollars 2 1/4 to Dollars
61 3/8 , Ford Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 67 and Chrysler Dollars 1 5/8 to
Dollars 61 1/2 .
Xerox impressed the market with better than expected earnings from its core
processing activities. The stock jumped Dollars 5 1/2 to Dollars 98 1/8 ,
well above its previous 52-week high of Dollars 93 1/2 .
Canada
Toronto surged in active dealings, in line with large increases on other
major world stock markets. The TSE 300 index ended 62.6 up at 4,554.8, some
eight points shy of the record high of 4,562.9 set on January 19.
Rises led declines by 507 to 339 after volume of 79.6m shares valued at
CDollars 1.1bn. Mining and conglomerates led the advance, jumping 2.93 and
2.74 per cent respectively. Golds climbed 2.32 per cent.
</TEXT>
