<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 94 / Government Bonds: Buyers move back into German bunds and
futures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONIA SHARPE and FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
German government bonds and futures built on last Friday's gains yesterday
as news of a further delay in the publication of the M3 data for December
prompted buyers to move back into the market. The March bund future on Liffe
traded at 100.53 in moderate volume in the late afternoon, up 0.16 points on
the day.
The Bundesbank said that the data would not be ready until later this week
due to technical difficulties caused by changes in their compilation.
Mr Klaus Baader, senior international economist at Lehman Brothers in
London, said that the delay had lessened the impact of a poor December
figure and was encouraging the market to focus on the M3 data for January,
which is expected to show an improvement.
The delay in the December number also prompted market participants to cast
their bets on whether the Bundesbank would cut interest rates at its
fortnightly council meeting on Thursday.
Dealers said that last week's favourable inflation data and the likelihood
of weak industrial production data for the fourth quarter had raised hopes
that the Bundesbank would cut rates by between a  1/4 and  1/2 point.
Some dealers said they believed that there was a 50 per cent to 70 per cent
chance of a cut on Thursday. However, some economists said that the
Bundesbank would be reluctant to cut rates during the current round of wage
talks in Germany.
UK government bonds rose by up to  1/2 point at the long end as the release
of a lower than expected M0 money supply figure for January revived hopes of
an early cut in UK interest rates.
'The soft M0 number showed that the economy is moving ahead rather than
flying ahead,' said Mr Kit Juckes at S. G. Warburg Securities. He added that
the recent media reports highlighting the competition in food prices gave
further support to the favourable outlook for inflation.
The market also appeared to be more comfortable now that most of the
unwanted supply from last week's gilts auction had found a home, Mr Juckes
said. The March long gilt future on Liffe traded at 119 1/4 in the late
afternoon, up  7/16 on the day.
Italian government bonds and futures held their ground as the market awaited
the results of 10 and 30-year bond auctions which were released just after
the market closed. The auction results showed net yields easing on both
issues. The March Liffe contract rose 0.33 on the day to 118.75.
Japanese government bonds and futures recovered their poise in London
trading after tumbling in Tokyo in reaction to the surge in the Japanese
stock market.
Expectations that the long-awaited fiscal stimulus package would be
announced this week had also contributed to the fall in Tokyo. Market
forecasts for the overall size of the fiscal stimulus range from Y14,000bn
to Y16,000bn.
The yield on the benchmark No 157 JGB rose by 10 basis points to 3.55 per
cent at the close in Tokyo but fell back to 3.53 per cent in London. The
March futures contract went as low as 112.74 in Tokyo before closing at
113.25, down 0.65 from Friday's closing level. However, it clawed back to
113.43 in London.
Mr Adam Chester, international bond strategist at Yamaichi International in
London, said he believed that the yield on the No 157 would not breach 3.6
per cent since the market was now looking cheap.
The prospect of a  1/2 point cut in the discount rate at the beginning of
March could help the yield to go back below 3 per cent, he added.
Longer-dated US Treasury bonds retreated yesterday after a firming trend in
commodities undercut the reassuring effect of comments by the Federal
Reserve Board chairman.
Late in the day, the benchmark 30-year government bond was  13/32 down at
100 1/16 , with the yield rising to 6.238 per cent. At the short end, the
two-year note edged  3/32 lower to 99 23/32 , to yield 4.132 per cent.
The market was pleased, but not surprised, by the testimony of Mr Alan
Greenspan, the Fed chairman, before the joint economic committee to
Congress.
In discussing the US economic outlook, he stressed the difficulty facing the
central bank in detecting latent inflationary pressures in time to contain
them. He cited data distortions arising from the recent cold weather, the
Los Angeles earthquake and modifications in methods used in compiling
employment figures.
But he emphasised that monetary policy 'must not over-stay accommodation',
which was taken as a signal that the Fed may soon move towards a more
restrictive bias.
The vigilant tone of his remarks, just ahead of the Fed's policy session
later this week, brought a modest improvement to the long end, which is most
sensitive to signs of higher inflation. At the short end, prices softened on
the prospects of a move to boost short-term rates.
In the afternoon, traders turned their attention to the commodity markets,
where prices for oil and basic metals were rebounding from earlier lows. In
response, the long bond retraced its earlier gains amid profit-taking and
slipped into negative territory.
</TEXT>
