<HEADLINE>
FT  01 FEB 94 / UK Company News: Canadians buy part of Rutland drinks arm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Rutland Trust, the financial and business services group, yesterday sold
part of Ben Shaw's, the Yorkshire soft drinks manufacturer, to Cott
Corporation of Canada, the rapidly expanding North American soft drinks
company.
Last week Cott entered the European market through a five-year agreement
with Cadbury Schweppes under which Cadbury bottling plants will produce
drinks for a newly-formed Cott subsidiary in Europe.
Cott is the leading producer of the private-label colas which are making big
inroads into the US market. It has grown rapidly by supplying North American
supermarket chains such as Wal-Mart with own-label colas. Profits at the
nine-month stage to end-October last year were more than doubled to CDollars
26.2m (Pounds 13.2m) on turnover that also more than doubled to CDollars
502m.
Mr Gerald Pencer, chief executive of Cott, said that the acquisition marked
Cott's move into the UK market and was part of its wider strategy of
developing into Europe.
The Canadian company is initially paying Pounds 6m for 51 per cent of Ben
Shaw's Pontefract canning line operation, which had a turnover of Pounds 40m
in the 11 months to the end of December last year.
Last August, Rutland paid Pounds 5.7m for 84 per cent of Ben Shaw's, a
family-owned firm that ran into trouble through over ambitious expansion.
Mr Michael Langdon, chairman of Rutland, said Cott had the option to buy a
further 31.5 per cent of the Pontefract operation in 12 months time for a
minimum of a further Pounds 5m and a maximum of Pounds 7.5m, depending on
1994 earnings. Rutland would retain 17.5 per cent.
Mr Langdon, who is also chairman of Ben Shaw's and will be joining the board
of Cott in the UK, said the company had rationalised its canning operations
and aggressively pursued sales to the big UK supermarkets.
</TEXT>
